{"title_page": "2016 Uri attack", "text_new": "{{Expert needed|1=India|reason=The article has been vandalised on multiple occasions. The facts needs to be cross-checked with sources.|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Terrorist attacks in India (since 2001)}}\n\nThere was an attack by four heavily armed terrorists on 18 September 2016, near the town of [[Uri, Jammu and Kashmir|Uri]] in the then Indian administered state of [[Jammu and Kashmir]]. It was reported as \"the deadliest attack on security forces in Kashmir in two decades\".<ref name=\"uri\">{{cite news|title=Militants attack Indian army base in Kashmir 'killing 17'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-37399969|accessdate=18 September 2016|work=|agency=BBC News|date=18 September 2016|location=}}</ref>  The terrorist group [[Jaish-e-Mohammed]] was involved in the planning and execution of the attack.<ref name=\"susperps\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-attack-jaish-suspects-in-hand-evidence-shown-to-envoy-3053717/|title=Uri attack: Jaish-e-Muhammad suspects in hand, evidence shown to envoy|date=28 September 2016|work=indianexpress.com}}</ref> At the time of the attack, the [[Kashmir Valley]] region was a centre of [[2016 Kashmir unrest|unrest]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/09/18/asia/india-kashmir-attack/|title=Soldiers killed in army base attack in Indian territory of Kashmir|work=CNN|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=21 September 2016|quote=After a few years of relative calm in Indian-administered Kashmir -- largely considered one of the world's most tumultuous geopolitical flashpoints since the India-Pakistan partition -- the region has been gripped by unrest for more than two months.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/32651887/suspected-rebels-attack-major-indian-army-base-in-kashmir|title=India blames Pakistan militants for Kashmir attack which killed 17|work=Yahoo|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=21 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919132241/https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/32651887/suspected-rebels-attack-major-indian-army-base-in-kashmir/ |archive-date=19 September 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Further|Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir|2016 Kashmir unrest}}\nSince 2015, the militants had increasingly taken to high-profile ''[[fidayeen]]'' attacks against the Indian security forces: in July 2015, three gunmen [[2015 Gurdaspur attack|attacked]] a bus and police station in [[Gurdaspur]] and earlier in 2016, 4\u20136 gunmen [[2016 Pathankot attack|attacked]] the [[Pathankot Air Force Station]]. Indian authorities blamed  [[Jaish-e-Mohammad]] for the latter attack.<ref name=Panda>\nAnkit Panda, [http://thediplomat.com/2016/09/gurdaspur-pathankot-and-now-uri-what-are-indias-options/ Gurdaspur, Pathankot, and Now Uri: What Are India's Options?], The Diplomat, 19 September 2016.\n</ref>\n\nAlso, since 8 July 2016, the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir has been undergoing continuous unrest following the killing of [[Burhan Wani]], a militant leader popular with the youth in the state.<ref name=DW>{{cite news|title=Indian troops suffer deadly Kashmir ambush|url=http://www.dw.com/en/indian-troops-suffer-deadly-kashmir-ambush/a-19559690}}</ref><ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=17 Indian Soldiers Killed by Militants in Kashmir|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/19/world/asia/17-indian-soldiers-killed-by-militants-in-kashmir.html?_r=1|publisher=[[New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name =CBC>{{cite news|title=17 Indian soldiers, 4 militants killed in Kashmir attack|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/kashmir-attack-1.3767723}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Militants sneak into Indian army base and mow down sleeping soldiers in Kashmir, killing 17|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-india-kashmir-20160918-snap-story.html}}</ref> The killing sparked violent protests against the Indian government in the valley,<ref name= time>{{cite web|title=A Terrorist Attack in Kashmir Sparks Fears of a Military Conflict Between India and Pakistan|url=http://time.com/4498891/kashmir-uri-attack-india-pakistan-military-conflict/}}</ref><ref name =AlJazeera1>{{cite news |title=17 Indian soldiers killed in attack on Kashmir base|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/09/20-dead-attack-army-base-kashmir-160918055803596.html}}</ref> leading to the  protests being described as the \"largest anti-India protests\" against Indian rule in recent years.<ref name =CBC/><ref name=WP>{{cite news|title=17 soldiers killed in attack at Indian army base in Kashmir|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/suspected-militants-attack-indian-army-base-in-kashmir/2016/09/17/23674c1a-7d4a-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=More than a dozen Indian soldiers killed in Kashmir attack|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/more-than-a-dozen-indian-soldiers-killed-in-kashmir-attack/}}</ref>\n\n==Attack==\nAt around 5:30&nbsp;a.m. on 18 September, four militants attacked an [[Indian Army]] brigade headquarters in [[Uri, Jammu and Kashmir|Uri]], near the [[Line of Control]] in a pre-dawn ambush. They were said to have lobbed 17 grenades in three minutes. As a rear administrative base camp with tents caught fire, 17 army personnel were killed during the attack. An additional 19-30 soldiers were reported to have been injured. A gun battle ensued lasting six hours, during which all the four militants were killed.<ref name=\"TOI19\"/><ref name=\"attack\">{{cite news|title=Tents set on fire, troops shot while coming out|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/militants-attack-army-battalion-in-uri-tents-set-on-fire-troops-shot-while-coming-out/article9120925.ece?homepage=true|accessdate=18 September 2016|work=The Hindu|agency=|date=18 September 2016|location=}}\n</ref><ref name=IndiaToday>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-inside-story-pashtun-map-pakistani-ammunition-jash-e-mohammed/1/767345.html Uri attack: An inside story of how it happened], India Today, 18 September 2016.</ref><ref name=plan>\n[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/sequence-of-the-uri-attack-the-plan-of-the-terrorists/articleshow/54397873.cms Sequence of the Uri attack & the plan of the terrorists], The Economic Times, 19 September 2016.</ref><ref name=Quint/>\nCombing operations continued to flush out additional terrorists thought to be alive.<ref name=\"uri\"/>\n\nMost of the soldiers killed were from the 10th battalion, [[Dogra Regiment]] (10 Dogra) and 6th battalion, [[Bihar Regiment]] (6 Bihar).<ref name=Quint>[https://www.thequint.com/india/2016/09/18/militants-attack-army-headquarters-in-uri-kashmir-firing-ongoing Uri Attack: Most of the 17 Soldiers Died in a Tent Fire], The Quint, 19 September 2016.</ref> One of the injured soldiers succumbed to his injuries on 19 September at RR Hospital in [[New Delhi]], followed by another soldier on 24 September, bringing the death toll to 19.<ref name=\"BSF_jawan\"/><ref name=\"succumbed\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/uri-attack-death-toll-touches-18-india-decides-to-isolate-pakistan-on-the-global-stage-3011334.html|title=Uri attack: Death toll touches 18, India decides to isolate Pakistan on the global stage&nbsp;\u2013 Firstpost|date=2016-09-19|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-19}}</ref>\n\nThe casualties were primarily believed to have occurred as a result of non-[[fire retardant]] transition tents. This was the time of a troops shift, whereby troops from 6 Bihar were replacing troops from 10 Dogra. The incoming troops were housed in tents, which are normally avoided in sensitive areas around the [[Line of Control|LoC]] like Uri. The attackers snuck into the camp breaching heavy security and seemed to know exactly where to strike. Seven of the personnel killed were support staff, including cooks and barbers.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/high-casualties-due-to-transition-tents/article9121325.ece High casualties due to transition tents], The Hindu, 19 September 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/uri-base-caught-off-guard-despite-specific-intel-army-investigates-1461701 Uri Base Caught Off-Guard Despite Specific Intel? Army Investigates], NDTV News, 20 September 2016.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nOn 19 September, Home Minister [[Rajnath Singh]], Defense Minister [[Manohar Parrikar]], [[Chief of the Army Staff (India)|Chief of the Army Staff]] [[Dalbir Singh]], National Security Advisor [[Ajit Doval]] and other officials of the Home and Defence ministries met to review the security situation in Kashmir, particularly in areas along the Line of Control.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-attack-rajnath-singh-manohar-parrikar-nsa-army-chief-meet-to-discuss-kashmir-3038767/|title=Uri attack: Rajnath Singh, Manohar Parrikar, NSA, Army chief meet to discuss Kashmir|agency=Press Trust of India|publisher=The Indian Express|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> The [[National Investigation Agency]] filed a [[first information report]] regarding the attack and took over the investigation from [[Jammu and Kashmir Police]] on 20 September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Uri-terror-attack-NIA-files-FIR-begins-probe/articleshow/54424217.cms|title=Uri terror attack: NIA files FIR, begins probe|publisher=Times of India|date=20 September 2016|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Pakistan International Airlines]] cancelled flights to some parts of Kashmir on 21 September in the aftermath of the attack.<ref>{{cite news|title=PIA cancels flights to Northern areas due to airspace restrictions|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1185715/pia-cancels-flights-northern-areas-due-air-space-restrictions/|publisher=[[The Express Tribune]]}}</ref> Security around the army installation in Uri was intensified following the attack, while soldiers on both the Indian and Pakistani side of Line of Control were placed on high alert.<ref>{{cite news|title=Troops on high alert along LoC|url=http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/troops-high-alert-along-loc/|publisher=[[Daily Excelsior]]|date=22 September 2016|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Postponement of SAARC summit===\nIn the wake of the attack, India cancelled its participation in the [[19th SAARC summit]] to be held in November in [[Islamabad]], Pakistan. The Ministry of External Affairs issued a statement, saying, \"India has conveyed to current SAARC Chair Nepal that increasing cross-border terrorist attacks in the region and growing interference in the internal affairs of Member States by one country have created an environment that is not conducive to the successful holding of the 19th SAARC Summit in Islamabad in November 2016.\" \"In the prevailing circumstances, the Government of India is unable to participate in the proposed Summit in Islamabad\", the statement said.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/india-pulls-out-of-saarc-summit-in-islamabad-1467221|title=PM Narendra Modi Will Not Attend SAARC Summit In Pakistan|work=ndtv.com}}</ref>\n\nOn India withdrawing from the scheduled SAARC summit in Islamabad, Pakistan's Foreign Office termed the withdrawal \"unfortunate\", and posted a rejoinder stating: \"As for the excuse used by India, the world knows that it is India that has been perpetrating and financing terrorism in Pakistan.\" The statement included a reference to Indian national [[Kulbhushan Jadhav]], detained by Pakistan for espionage, and accused India of violating international laws by interfering inside Pakistan.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1189456/india-pulls-saarc-summit-islamabad/|title=India pulls out of SAARC summit in Islamabad|date=27 September 2016|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nLater, Afghanistan, Bangladesh and Bhutan also withdrew from the summit.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/dhaka-kabul-thimphu-too-blame-islamabad-saarc-summit-to-be-called-off-3054953/ | title=SAARC summit to be called off as Dhaka, Kabul and Thimphu too slam Islamabad | work=The Indian Express | date=29 September 2016 | accessdate=24 September 2016 | author=Roy, Shubhajit | location=New Delhi}}</ref><ref name = \"HT\">{{cite web|title=SAARC summit collapses after India and three other members pull out|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/saarc-summit-collapses-after-india-and-3-other-members-pull-out/story-kIMWfSqirGLzB6MEfuS3CN.html|website=Hindustan Times|accessdate=29 September 2016|date=28 September 2016}}</ref> On 30 September 2016,  Pakistan stated that the summit scheduled for 9 and 10 November in Islamabad would be held on an alternative date.<ref>{{cite web|title=SAARC summit 'postponed indefinitely'|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/saarc-summit-postponed-indefinitely/article9170272.ece|work=The Hindu|date=1 October 2016|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Indian retaliation===\n{{See also|2016 Indian Line of Control strike}}\nOn 28 September, eleven days after the attack, the Indian Army conducted retaliatory \"surgical strikes\" on what it termed \"launch-pads\" used by militants in [[Pakistan administered Kashmir]].<ref name=Economist>[https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21708302-there-still-more-smoke-fire-heated-exchanges-how-long-reversing-roles?zid=306&ah=1b164dbd43b0cb27ba0d4c3b12a5e227 India and Pakistan: Reversing roles], The Economist, 8 October 2016.</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Jamal |first=Umair |title=India Pakistan Conflict: what is next for the historic foes? |publisher=Al Jazeera Centre for Studies |date=17 November 2016 |url=http://studies.aljazeera.net/mritems/Documents/2016/11/17/fa613052c2b84f21a192cb060ef4601d_100.pdf |p=3}}</ref> Indian Director General of Military Operations (DGMO) Lt Gen Ranbir Singh said that it had made a preemptive strike against \"terrorist teams\" who were preparing to \"carry out infiltration and conduct terrorist strikes inside Jammu and Kashmir and in various metros in other states\".<ref name=BBC2>{{cite web|title=Kashmir attack: India 'launches strikes against militants'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37504308|website=BBC News|accessdate=29 September 2016|date=29 September 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' while citing Indian reports, reported that Indian commandos crossed the Line of Control and struck at the safe houses, allegedly killing approximately 150 pakistan sponsored terrorists.<ref name=Economist/> Pakistani officials on  next day did press conference with National and International media on the site. They rejected Indian claims and asserted that Indian Army never crossed the Line of Control.\n\n===Bilateral boycott===\nFollowing the uproar after the Uri attack, Indian Motion Picture Producers Association (IMPPA) decided to ban all Pakistani actors, actresses and technicians working in India till the situation returns to normal.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/imppa-passes-resolution-temporarily-ban-pakistani-artists-india-twitter-reacts-695956|title=IMPPA passes resolution to temporarily ban Pakistani artists in India; Twitter reacts|first=Suparno|last=Sarkar|work=ibtimes.co.in}}</ref> Bollywood artists were divided towards the ban with some justifying it while some questioning its benefits.<ref name=\"firstpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/salman-khan-nana-patekar-ranbir-kapoor-heres-what-bollywood-said-on-pak-actors-ban-3031294.html|title=Salman Khan, Nana Patekar, Ranbir Kapoor: Here's what Bollywood said on Pak actors ban - Firstpost|date=3 October 2016|work=firstpost.com}}</ref> Indian TV entertainment channel ''[[Zindagi (TV channel)|Zindagi]]'' announced discontinuation of airing Pakistani TV shows on the channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/after-pak-show-ban-zindagi-channel-to-view-indian-television-content-3063351/|title=After Pak Show ban, Zindagi Channel to bank on Indian, Turkish content|date=3 October 2016|work=indianexpress.com}}</ref> The Pakistani government responded in October with a blanket ban on all Indian television and radio programming in Pakistan.<ref name=\"bans_Indian\">{{cite news|title=Pakistan bans all Indian TV and radio as tensions mount|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37731089|accessdate=21 October 2016|work=|agency=BBC News|date=21 October 2016|location=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI), the national governing body for cricket in India, ruled out the possibility of reviving bilateral cricket ties with Pakistan in the near future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/bcci-chief-anurag-thakur-says-no-question-of-playing-cricket-with-pakistan-after-uri-attack-3018372.html|title=Uri attack aftermath: BCCI chief Anurag Thakur says no question of playing cricket with Pakistan - Firstpost|date=23 September 2016|work=firstpost.com}}</ref> BCCI also asked the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) to not group Indian and Pakistan cricket teams together in international tournaments, keeping in mind border tensions between the two countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/news/india-pakistan-shouldnt-be-grouped-together-in-international-events-bcci-to-icc-cricket-1468631|title=India, Pakistan Shouldn't be Grouped Together in International Events: BCCI to ICC \u2013 NDTV Sports|first=|last=NDTVSports.com|work=ndtv.com}}</ref> [[Badminton Association of India]], the governing body for badminton in India, decided to boycott the Pakistan International Series scheduled to be held in Islamabad in October, as an act of \"solidarity\" with the government's diplomatic offensive against Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/other-sports/indian-badminton-association-boycotts-series-in-pakistan/story-yNlpCUO4kTGqHNrQqLOVLI.html|title=Indian badminton association boycotts series in Pakistan|date=2 October 2016|work=hindustantimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n\nAn initial investigation into the attack indicated that there were several procedural lapses at the camp. According to the standard security procedures, any tall grass and bushes around vital security installations should be trimmed. However, this procedure was not followed by the Uri camp which might have allowed terrorists to sneak into the camp undetected using the tall grass and bushes around the perimeter. In addition, the probe also indicated that two manned guard posts failed to detect the intrusion because the coordination between them might have been poor. It also indicated that the terrorists had infiltrated the Indian territory through [[Haji Pir Pass]] on the intervening night of 16\u201317 September and stayed in Sukhdar village which is located at a vantage point that allows an unhindered view of the layout of the camp as well as movement of the personnel in it.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Uri-terror-attack-Many-procedural-lapses-at-Army-camp-says-initial-probe/articleshow/54466648.cms| title=Uri terror attack: Many procedural lapses at Army camp, says initial probe], Times of India, 22 September 2016.}}</ref>\n\n===Perpetrators===\nThe Director General of military operations, Lieutenant-General Ranbir Singh, said that there was evidence{{clarify|date=December 2017}}{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} that the attackers belonged to [[Jaish-e-Mohammad]].<ref name=\"congressional\">{{Cite journal| last = Cronin| first = Audrey Kurth|author2=Huda Aden |author3=Adam Frost |author4=Benjamin Jones | title = Foreign Terrorist Organizations| journal = CRS Report for Congress| volume = | issue = | pages= 40\u201343  | publisher = Congressional Research Service| location = Washington, D.C.| date = 2004-02-06| url = https://fas.org/irp/crs/RL32223.pdf| accessdate = 2009-12-02}}</ref> He established a hotline contact with his Pakistani counterpart and conveyed India's serious concern on the issue.<ref name=IndiaToday/><ref name=web>[http://www.timesofindia.com/india/Jaish-terrorists-behind-Uri-attack-had-items-with-Pakistani-markings-Army/articleshow/54392506.cms Jaish terrorists behind Uri attack, had items with Pakistani markings: Army], Times Of India, 18 September 2016.</ref> Singh also stated that the militants used [[incendiary ammunition]] to set fire to the tents.<ref name=IndiaToday/><ref name=\"NIA begins\">[http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/uri-attack-nia-team-begins-probe-visits-encounter-site/article9125398.ece NIA team begins probe, visits Uri encounter site], The Hindu, 20 September 2016.</ref>\n\nThe Indian Ministry of External Affairs said:\n\n{{quote|In the recent incidents, we have recovered a number of items that include GPS from the bodies of terrorists with coordinates that indicate the point and time of infiltration across the LoC and the subsequent route to the terror attack site; grenades with Pakistani markings; communication matrix sheets; communication equipment; and other stores made in Pakistan, including food, medicines and clothes.<ref name=envoy/>}}\n\nWhilst, on 29 September, National Investigation Agency officials said:\n\n{{Quote|text=Until now, little hard evidence has emerged to link the perpetrators of the terror attack in Uri to specific jihadist groups in Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-terror-attack-soldiers-dead-nia-probe-results-pakistan-lashkar-planned-3041576/|title=Uri attack probe: Terrorists locked soldiers in cook house, store|date=2016-09-21|newspaper=The Indian Express|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n}}\n\nFormer Pakistani General [[Pervez Musharraf]] said the weapons that India reported as used by militants, and reported to have Pakistani markings, could be procured anywhere in the world, not just in Pakistan.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|title=Pervez Musharraf blasts on \"double standards\" of India on terrorism|url=http://channel24.pk/breaking-news/2016/09/21/pervez-musharraf-blasts-india-terrorism/}}</ref> Musharraf further said since many American weapons had inadvertently fallen into the hands of the [[Taliban]], it is possible for Pakistani weapons to have been acquired by the perpetrators without Pakistani involvement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Uri attack: Pervez Musharraf denies terrorists used Pakistani weapons|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-pervez-musharraf-denies-terrorists-used-pakistani-weapons/1/769404.html}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September, the Indian Army said that two Pakistani nationals{{efn|The two individuals were identified as Ahasan Kursheed of [[Khaliana Kalan]]{{coord|34|4|30|N|73|53|10|E|name=Khaliana Kalan|display=none}} and Faisal Hussain Awan of [[Potha Bainsi|Potha Jahangir]]{{coord|33|7|51|N|73|52|31|E|name=Potha|display=none}}.}} from [[Pakistan administered Kashmir]] were arrested by the [[Border Security Force]] in the Uri sector. They were said to have been recruited by Jaish-e-Mohammad two years ago for the purpose of acting as guides to infiltrating groups in the Uri sector. These guides themselves did not have a role in the Uri attack. They were being questioned for gathering intelligence about infiltration attempts.<ref>\n[http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-attack-two-jem-guides-from-pok-arrested-army-3048685/ Two JeM \u2018guides\u2019 arrested in Uri: Army], The Indian Express, 25 September 2016.</ref> Pakistan denied these allegations.<ref name=\"SSA\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1286447/|title=Two guides from Muzaffarabad facilitated Uri attackers, India tells Pakistan|work=Dawn|first=Syed Sammer|last=Abbas|date=27 September 2016|accessdate=28 September 2016|quote=Pakistan on Tuesday promptly rejected Indian allegations of its involvement in the Uri army base attack, soon after Indian authorities said they had shared \"evidence\" with Pakistan High Commissioner to New Delhi Abdul Basit.}}</ref> On 26 February 2017, India's National Investigative Agency (NIA) decided to file a closure report after failing to find any evidence against the two men whom they accused of facilitating the Uri army base attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1339596/india-fails-substantiate-claim-pakistans-involvement-uri-attack/|title=India fails to substantiate claim of Pakistan's involvement in Uri attack - The Express Tribune|date=26 February 2017|publisher=|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 October 2016, the Indian media reported that street \"posters\" in [[Gujranwala]], Pakistan, attributed to [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] (LeT) claimed responsibility for the Uri attack.<ref name=\"respperp\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/exclusive-uri-attack-in-posters-pasted-on-gujaranwala-streets-lashkar-claims-responsibility-3101738/|title=In posters pasted on Gujranwala streets, Lashkar claims responsibility of Uri Attack|date=25 October 2016|newspaper=The Indian Express}}</ref><ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-let-terror-hafiz-saeed-pakistan/1/794879.html Posters in Pakistan town show Lashkar claiming responsibility for Uri attack], India Today, 25 October 2016.</ref> The posters claimed that one of LeT's fighters Mohammad Anas, code-named Abu Saraqa, died in the Uri attack, and there would be a funeral prayer followed by a speech by the LeT chief [[Hafiz Muhammad Saeed|Hafiz Saeed]] on 25 October. The poster also claimed death of 177 Indian soldiers in Uri attack. After the images of the poster circulated on the Internet, the organisation claimed that it was a hoax. [[Abbas Nasir]], the former editor of ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]'', confirmed the report about the posters on Twitter but stated that the funeral prayers have been postponed.<ref name=confirm>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Lashkar-claims-responsibility-for-Uri-terror-attack/articleshowprint/55047490.cms?null Lashkar-e-Taiba claims responsibility for Uri terror attack], The Times of India, 25 October 2016.</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n\n===India===\nPrime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and members of his cabinet condemned the attack.<ref name=\"uri\"/> Minister of Defence Manohar Parrikar and Indian Army chief General Dalbir Singh visited [[Kashmir valley|Kashmir]] soon after the attack to assess the ongoing military operations and review the security situation in the region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/parrikar-army-chief-visit-kashmir-review-security/|title=Parrikar, Army chief visit Kashmir, review security|publisher=Daily Excelsior|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Parrikar instructed the army to take firm action against those responsible for the attack and also stated that the deaths of the soldiers \"will not go in vain.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/after-uri-attack-manohar-parrikar-instructs-army-to-take-firm-action-1460286|title=After Uri Attack, Manohar Parrikar Instructs Army To Take 'Firm Action'|publisher=Daily Excelsior|date=18 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Home Minister Rajnath Singh accused Pakistan of what he called its \"continued and direct support to terrorism and terrorist groups,\" calling Pakistan a \"terrorist state\" that should be \"isolated.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/isolate-terrorist-state-pakistan-says-rajnath-singh-after-kashmir-attack-1460127|title=Isolate 'Terrorist State' Pakistan, Says Rajnath Singh After Kashmir Attack|work=ndtv.com}}</ref> Minister of State for Defence Subhash Bhamre stated that the \"entire nation was traumatised\" over the death of the soldiers and was \"united in this hour of grief.\" He also stated that the Prime Minister, Home Minister and Defence Minister had come to a conclusion that some sort of a \"response\" needs to be given to Pakistan.<ref name=\"Bhamre\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/uri-terror-attack-mos-defence-bhamre-confirms-death-toll-still-17/story-XdSsKIzLVLxzm1tCOM1GwO.html |title=MoS defence denies reports of 3 more Uri attack deaths |publisher=Hindustan Times |date=19 September 2016 |accessdate=19 September 2016}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Minister of State for External Affairs]] [[Sushma Swaraj]] and former Army chief [[Vijay Kumar Singh]] stated that India will give a \"befitting reply\" to the attack. He called upon the Indian Armed Forces to scale up their security and described a cold and calculated response as the need of the hour. He also called for an investigation into the shortcomings which led to the attack while stating that the Army should decide its response \"coolly\" with proper planning.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/india-will-give-a-cold-calculated-and-befitting-reply-says-general-vk-singh-on-uri-attack/381581/|title=India will give a cold, calculated, and befitting reply, says General VK Singh on Uri attack|publisher=The Financial Express|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/VK-Singh-calls-for-probe-into-lacunas-which-led-to-Uri-attack/articleshow/54405818.cms|title=VK Singh calls for probe into lacunas which led to Uri attack|agency=Press Trust of India|publisher=Times of India|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Many{{vague|date=September 2016}} Indian politicians and public figures have condemned the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Uri-terror-attack-Demands-rise-for-befitting-reply-to-Pakistan/articleshow/54404645.cms|title=Uri terror attack: Demands rise for 'befitting reply' to Pakistan|first=Shailaja|last=Neelakantan|publisher=Times of India|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Former Indian diplomats and foreign policy experts{{who|date=September 2016}} have said that India had been driven to the wall and that a measured and effective response was needed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/uri-attack-india-driven-to-the-wall-say-diplomats/article9121284.ece|title=Uri attack: India driven to the wall, say diplomats|work=The Hindu|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref> The opposition [[Indian National Congress]] has said that there was no more scope for constructive dialogue with Pakistan.<ref>[http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/no-scope-for-constructive-dialogue-with-pak-post-uri-attack-congress-116091900885_1.html No scope for constructive dialogue with Pak post-Uri attack: Congress], Business Standard, 19 September 2016.\n</ref>\n\nLater on the same day, India called upon the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] to urge Pakistan to put an end to cross-border infiltration and dismantle the non-state militant infrastructure since the likes of [[Hafeez Saeed]] (the chief of [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]]) and [[Syed Salahuddin]] (the chief of [[Hizbul Mujahideen]]) can hold huge rallies in Pakistan's main cities. It suggested that active support for such groups has become the \"new normal\" in Pakistan. It claimed that \"zero tolerance\" to non-state militancy was an international obligation.<ref>[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/active-support-for-terrorists-like-hafiz-saeed-syed-salahuddin-new-normal-in-pakistan-india-at-un-human-rights-council/articleshow/54416144.cms Active support for terrorists like Hafiz Saeed, Syed Salahuddin new normal in Pakistan: India at UN Human Rights Council], The Economic Times, 20 September 2016.</ref> The Indian government summoned the Pakistani envoy and handed him a dossier that alleged Pakistani involvement as well as a warning that Pakistan needs to rein in militants they say operate from Pakistan.<ref name=envoy>[http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/days-after-uri-attack-india-summons-pakistan-envoy-abdul-basit-1464745 3 Days After Uri Attack, India Hands Pakistan Envoy Evidence And A Warning], NDTV News, 21 September 2016.</ref>\n\nOn 24 September, Prime Minister Modi formally responded to the attack during a BJP rally in Kozhikode, Kerala; in his address, he charged Pakistan with responsibility for the attack, saying that India would \"never forget\" Uri and would \"leave no stone unturned to isolate Pakistan in the world.\" He called upon the citizens of both India and Pakistan to fight against poverty. \"I want to say that India is ready for a war... India is ready for a war on poverty. Let both countries fight to see who would eradicate poverty first... I want to tell the youth of Pakistan, let's have a war on ending unemployment... I want to call out to the children in Pakistan, let's declare war on illiteracy. Let's see who wins.\"<ref name=\"Kozhikode\">{{cite news|title=PM Modi speaks to people of Pakistan: Let us go to war against poverty, unemployment... let's see who wins|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/pm-narendra-modi-speaks-to-the-people-of-pakistan-lets-go-to-war-against-poverty-unemployment-lets-see-who-wins-3048329/|accessdate=27 September 2016|work=|agency=The Indian Express|date=25 September 2016|location=}}</ref>\n\nIn further responding to the attack, on 26 September, the Indian government stated it would exercise its rights under the 1960 [[Indus Waters Treaty]] to the full and would expand its utilisation of its rivers flowing through Jammu and Kashmir. Talks under the aegis of the Permanent Indus Commission, to which any disputes may be submitted, would cease \"until terror comes to an end.\" The body had most recently met in July 2016.<ref name=\"suspend_Indus\">{{cite news|title=India suspends talks on Indus water pact|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-likely-to-suspend-indus-water-commission-talks/article9150223.ece|accessdate=27 September 2016|work=|agency=The Hindu|date=26 September 2016|location=}}</ref> The government subsequently stated it would review Pakistan's most-favoured-nation (MFN) trade status, which India had granted in 1996.<ref name=\"MFN\">{{cite news|title=India to review MFN status to Pakistan on Thursday|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-to-review-pakistans-mfn-status-on-thursday/article9153752.ece?homepage=true|accessdate=27 September 2016|work=|agency=The Hindu|date=27 September 2016|location=}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan===\nPakistan's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Pakistan)|Foreign Ministry]] rejected India's allegations of involvement in the attack. The ministry asserted that India had a \"tendency\" of accusing Pakistan for incidents inside its territory, adding that \"in the past many Indians were involved in the terrorist acts for which India had blamed Pakistan.\"<ref name=Dawn/> The ministry deemed Indian statements as \"vitriolic.\"<ref name =BBC3>{{cite news|title=Kashmir attack: Pakistan hits back at India accusations|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37405719|accessdate=19 September 2016|work=|agency=BBC News|date=19 September 2016|location=}}</ref> Pakistan's foreign ministry also accused the Indian government of trying to deflect attention from the [[Human rights abuses in Jammu and Kashmir|human rights situation in Kashmir]], with a reference to the [[2016 Kashmir unrest|ongoing civil unrest]]. It said the situation in Indian-administered Kashmir was \"not of Pakistan's making but a direct consequence of illegal Indian occupation and a long history of atrocities\", and that India's reaction of accusing Pakistan without investigations was \"deplorable.\"<ref name =BBC3/>\n\nDuring a press conference in [[London]], Pakistani Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] linked the incident to the recent unrest and human rights issues in Kashmir.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/uri-attack-could-be-a-reaction-to-situation-in-kashmir-sharif/article9142318.ece|title=Uri attack could be a 'reaction' to situation in Kashmir, says Sharif|work=The Hindu|date=24 September 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> Interior Minister [[Nisar Ali Khan]] said there were several contradictions within [[Indian media]] reports over the evidence, and claimed India was imposing censorship when their \"lies were exposed.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1187406/run-govt-bring-brahamdagh-back-interpol/|title=Govt to bring Brahamdagh back through Interpol|work=The Express Tribune|date=24 September 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://aaj.tv/2016/09/india-has-no-evidence-nisar/|title=India has no evidence: Nisar|work=AAJ News|date=24 September 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> Defence Minister [[Khawaja Muhammad Asif]] termed the attack an \"inside job\", saying that no proof was provided substantiating India's allegations, and said India was not serious about solving the Kashmir dispute.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1286423/|title=Uri attack an inside job, says Khawaja Asif|work=Dawn|first=Adil Aziz|last=Khanzada|date=27 September 2016|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/india-staged-uri-attacks-says-pakistan-defence-minister-khawaja-asif-695528|title=India staged Uri attacks, says Pakistan Defence Minister Khawaja Asif|work=International Business Times|date=27 September 2016|accessdate=28 September 2016|first=Mangala|last=Dilip}}</ref> Pakistan's envoy in New Delhi, [[Abdul Basit (diplomat)|Abdul Basit]], told India's Foreign Secretary [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar|S. Jaishankar]] that India sought to divert world attention from state atrocities in Kashmir by blaming the attack on Pakistan. Basit also added that if India was serious about the investigations, it should not avoid allowing independent investigators to probe it.<ref name=\"SSA\"/>\n\nIn the hours following the attack, Pakistan's military established a [[hotline]] with the Indian military. The Pakistani military rejected Indian accusations, saying that infiltration was not possible across the heavily guarded LOC. Pakistan's Director General of Military Operations also asked the Indian military to provide actionable intelligence.<ref name=Dawn>{{cite news|title=Pakistan rejects India's allegations of involvement in terrorist attack in held Kashmir|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1284555|publisher=[[Dawn News]]}}</ref>\n\nPakistan's [[Chief of Army Staff (Pakistan)|Chief of Army Staff]] [[Raheel Sharif]] claimed that India was propagating a \"hostile narrative\" in response the attack and also stated that the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistani armed forces]] were \"prepared to respond to the entire spectrum of direct and indirect threat.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=India propagating 'hostile narrative' about Uri attack: Pak Army chief|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/india-propagating-hostile-narrative-about-uri-attack-pak-army-chief/story-LFHNi2z8BFDPow4xtjMGSM.html|accessdate=19 September 2016|work=Hindustan Times|date=19 September 2016|location=}}</ref>\n\nIn response to India's suspension of cooperation over the Indus Waters Treaty, [[Sartaj Aziz]] said India could not revoke the treaty unilaterally as per the IWT's provisions and international laws, and said such a move would be taken as an act of \"war and hostilities.\" Aziz said Pakistan would approach the United Nations Security Council in that event.<ref>[http://gulfnews.com/news/asia/pakistan/violation-of-water-treaty-risks-war-senior-pakistan-official-warns-1.1903026 Violation of water treaty risks war, senior Pakistan official warns], Gulf News, 28 September 2016</ref>\n\nOn India withdrawing from the scheduled SAARC summit in Islamabad, Pakistan's Foreign Office termed the withdrawal \"unfortunate\" and posted a rejoinder stating: \"As for the excuse used by India, the world knows that it is India that has been perpetrating and financing terrorism in Pakistan.\" The statement included a reference to Indian national [[Kulbhushan Yadav]], detained by Pakistan for espionage, and accused India of violating international laws by interfering inside Pakistan.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Other states===\n* {{flag|Afghanistan}}&nbsp;\u2013 [[Afghan Ambassador to India]] [[Shaida Mohammad Abdali]] condemned the attack. Pledging his nation's support to Prime Minister Narendra Modi's call for a strong and firm action against the perpetrators, Ambassador Abdali said: \"We fully support PM Modi's call for strong and firm action against those who terrorise people, and those who use terrorism as an instrument of foreign policy; seeing this for many years. Whoever uses terrorism shouldn't only be isolated but also held accountable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/uri-attack-afghan-envoy-calls-for-joint-strategy-to-fight-terrorist-groups-116091901080_1.html|title=Uri attack: Afghan envoy calls for joint strategy to fight terrorist groups|first=|last=ANI|date=19 September 2016|publisher=|via=Business Standard}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Armenia}}&nbsp;\u2013 Armenia condemned the attack and expressed condolences to \"families of killed and friendly people of India\".<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Bahrain}}&nbsp;\u2013 Bahrain's Ministry of Foreign Affairs affirmed the nation's \"full support to the friendly Republic of India in their actions to counter terrorism\" and called for \"concerted efforts to eliminate it (terrorism) and cut off its funding.\"<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Bangladesh}}&nbsp;\u2013Bangladesh High Commissioner to India Syed Muazzem Ali <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofa.gov.bd/foreign-secretary/mr-syed-muazzem-ali|title=Mr. Syed Muazzem Ali {{!}} Welcome to MOFA Website|website=www.mofa.gov.bd|access-date=2016-09-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927021916/http://www.mofa.gov.bd/foreign-secretary/mr-syed-muazzem-ali|archive-date=27 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> condemned the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/uri-terror-attack-bangladesh-stands-with-india-says-envoy-1293717.html|title=Uri Terror Attack: Bangladesh Stands With India, Says Envoy|date=19 September 2016|author=|work=news18.com}}</ref> Bangladesh&nbsp;\u2013 MOFA has not yet released a press release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofa.gov.bd/media/press-release|title=Press Release {{!}} Welcome to MOFA Website|website=www.mofa.gov.bd|access-date=2016-09-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912232224/http://mailto:mission.agartala@mofa.gov.bd/media/press-release|archive-date=12 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The country has also withdrawn from the 19th [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation|SAARC]] summit scheduled to be held in Islamabad, Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/india-pulls-out-of-saarc-meet-as-it-looks-to-isolate-pakistan-diplomatically-after-uri-terror-attack-262520.html|title=India Pulls Out Of SAARC, Bangladesh & Afghanistan Follow. Pak Heads Towards Total Isolation|access-date=2016-09-29}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Bhutan}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Foreign Ministry issued a statement that read: \"Bhutan strongly condemns terrorism in all its forms and stands with India in the fight against terrorism. Such heinous acts of terrorism calls for the need to step up international cooperation to combat the scourge of terrorism that poses a severe threat to the peace and stability of all countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/world/bhutan-condemns-uri-attack_1931286.html|title=Bhutan condemns Uri attack|work=Zee News|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Canada}}&nbsp;\u2013 Acting High Commissioner Jess Dutton issued a statement condemning the attack and extending Canada's condolences to the victims and their families. \"We are appalled by these attacks and stand with the Government of India in the fight against terrorism.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/india-inde/highlights-faits/2016/2016-09-19_Canada-condemns-attack_condamne-attaque_Uri.aspx?lang=en | title=Canada condemns attack on Indian Army camp at Uri | work=Government of Canada: Canada in India | date=19 September 2016 | accessdate=20 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218192746/http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/india-inde/highlights-faits/2016/2016-09-19_Canada-condemns-attack_condamne-attaque_Uri.aspx?lang=en | archive-date=18 December 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* {{flag|China}}&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Foreign Ministry]] issued a statement condemning the attack and expressed sympathy towards the families of the slain soldiers as well as the injured soldiers. It also expressed concerns about rising tensions in the Kashmir region and called upon India and Pakistan to hold dialogue and consultations in order to solve their differences and counter-terrorism operations.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-china-pakistan-india/1/767962.html | title=China condemns Uri attack, but wants India, Pakistan to have 'dialogue'| work=India Today | first=Ananth |last=Krishnan |date= 19 September 2016 |accessdate= 19 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|France}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Development issued a statement condemning the attack and calling for a peaceful settlement to disputes in Kashmir. \"France condemns in the firmest terms the terrible terrorist attack committed on 18 September against an Indian Army camp in the Kashmir region. It expresses its condolences to the families of the 17 Indian soldiers killed in this attack. France stands beside India in the struggle against terrorism. It calls on each state to effectively fight against terrorist groups operating on its territory or from its territory against other countries. France reaffirms its commitment for a peaceful and structured settlement of differences in the region of Kashmir.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/dossiers-pays/inde/http-publication-diplomatie-gouv-fr-fr-dossiers-pays-inde-evenements/article/inde-attaque-terroriste-18-09-16 | title=Inde&nbsp;\u2013 Attaque terrorist (18 September 2016) (fr) | work=France&nbsp;\u2013 Diplomacy | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref> France also called for \"decisive actions\" against anti-India terrorist organisations, including [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]], [[Jaish-e-Mohammed]] and [[Hizbul Mujahideen]].<ref name=\"toi-21sep\">{{cite news|title=Condemning Uri terror attack, France, Russia score direct hits against Pakistan|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Condemning-Uri-terror-attack-France-Russia-score-direct-hits-against-Pakistan/articleshow/54429098.cms|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=The Times of India|date=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Germany}}&nbsp;\u2013 Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]] condemned the attack and said, \"our thoughts are with the families of the murdered soldiers and with the many people who have been injured, some seriously.\"<ref name=\"FE\">{{cite news|title=Uri terror attack: After Russia, now Germany and Japan stand with India; condemn terrorist strike|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/uri-terror-attack-after-russia-now-germany-and-japan-stand-with-india-condemn-terrorist-strike/383379/|accessdate=20 September 2016|date=20 September 2016|work=The Financial Express}}</ref> He added, \"Germany stands resolutely at India's side in the fight against terrorism. At the Indo-German counterterrorism consultations, which will take place in a few days' time, we will further discuss the threats to our two countries' societies.\".<ref name=\"FE\"/>\n* {{flag|Italy}}&nbsp;\u2013 Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Paolo Gentiloni]] condemned the attack \"in Indian-administered Kashmir.\" He offered \"deepest condolences to the families of the victims and to the Indian authorities,\" also affirming \"Italy's solidarity with India in a common fight against terrorism to promote peace and security in the world.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.esteri.it/mae/en/sala_stampa/archivionotizie/comunicati/2016/09/l-italia-condanna-l-attacco-terroristico.html | title=Italy condemns Kashmir terror attack. Minister Gentiloni offers his condolences | work=Farnesina (Ministry of Foreign Affairs and External Cooperation) | date=19 September 2016 | accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Japan}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement which read: \"The Government of Japan strongly condemns the terrorist attack on the Indian Base in Uri, Jammu and Kashmir, and extends its sincere condolences to those who lost their lives and their bereaved families, and expresses its heartfelt sympathy to those who were injured.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Japan, Russia condemns Uri terror attack, express solidarity with India|url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/japan-russia-condemns-uri-terror-attack-express-solidarity-154319032.html|accessdate=20 September 2016|publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]|date=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Maldives}}&nbsp;\u2013 Maldives{{who|date=September 2016}} condemned the attack, saying that it has \"always condemned international terrorism, especially those originating from outside, defeating and eliminating which requires international collaboration and cooperation in good faith.\"<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Mauritius}}&nbsp;\u2013 Mauritius{{who|date=September 2016}} condemned the attack and said that it \"stands in solidarity with the Government of India and with all those committed to the fight against terrorism.\"<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Mongolia}}&nbsp;\u2013 Mongolia{{who|date=September 2016}} expressed its deep regret in regards to the attack and said that the \"terrorist attack must not be a disruption of efforts for strengthening the regional stability and mutual understanding in the region.\"<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Nepal}}&nbsp;\u2013 In a message to his Indian counterpart, Prime Minister [[Pushpa Kamal Dahal|Prachanda]] said he was of the firm belief that the perpetrators behind this heinous act will be brought to justice at the earliest. He reiterated the Nepali government's position of unequivocally condemning non-state militancy in all its forms and manifestations and said that such acts must be firmly and resolutely dealt with. Prachanda also extended his heartfelt condolences and sympathies to the bereaved families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indialivetoday.com/nepal-condemns-uri-attack/32471.html|title=Nepal condemns Uri attack|date=19 September 2016|work=indialivetoday.com|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322125741/http://www.indialivetoday.com/nepal-condemns-uri-attack/32471.html|archive-date=22 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mofa.gov.np/press-release-terrorist-attack-uri/|title=Press Release on the Terrorist Attack in Uri|date=2016-09-19|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-20}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Qatar}}&nbsp;\u2013 Qatar{{who|date=September 2016}} condemned the attack, stressing its \"condemnation of such criminal acts which aim to undermine security and stability.\"<ref name=ibt>{{cite news|last1=Bhat|first1=Aditya|title=International community supports India, strongly condemns Uri attack|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/uri-attack-here-how-international-community-responded-694476|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=21 September 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Russia}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Russian Foreign Ministry issued a statement condemning the attacks, and also offered condolences to the families of victims. The Ministry also expressed concern about the terrorist attacks near the Line of Control stating, \"We are also concerned about the fact that, according to New Delhi, the army base near Uri was attacked from Pakistani territory.\" The ministry added, \"We believe that this criminal act will be investigated properly, and that its organisers and perpetrators will be held accountable. We confirm our continued support for the Indian government's counterterrorism efforts.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Korablinov|first1=Alexander|title=Russia strongly condemns Uri attack|url=https://in.rbth.com/world/2016/09/19/russia-strongly-condemns-uri-attack_631299|website=Russia & India Report|accessdate=29 September 2016|language=en-IN|date=19 September 2016}}</ref> On 19 September, Indian media claimed that Russia was cancelling a joint military exercise with Pakistan that had been scheduled to begin on 24 September.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uri Attack fallout: Russia calls off military exercise with Pakistan|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/uri-attack-fallout-russia-calls-of-military-exercise-with-pakistan/382372/|website=The Financial Express|accessdate=29 September 2016|date=19 September 2016}}</ref> However, Russian forces arrived in Pakistan on 23 September and commenced the exercises as scheduled.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1186889/russian-forces-arrive-pakistan-first-ever-joint-military-exercise/|title=Russian forces arrive in Pakistan for first-ever joint military exercise|work=Express Tribune|date=23 September 2016|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Saudi Arabia}}&nbsp;\u2013 Saudi Arabia{{who|date=September 2016}} expressed its \"strong condemnation and denunciation of the terrorist attack that targeted an Indian military base in the Uri area of north Kashmir, killing and wounding dozens.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Caution and clamour on Uri response|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1160921/jsp/nation/story_109374.jsp#.V-KMklR97IU|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|date=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Singapore}}&nbsp;\u2013 Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] condemned the attack during an official visit to India on 4 October. \"Singapore condemns terrorism in all forms and we express condolences to the victims of the terror attack in Uri.\"<ref name=\"Singapore\">{{cite news|title=Singapore condemns terrorism in all forms|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/singapore-condemns-terrorism-in-all-forms/article9184259.ece|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=|agency=The Hindu|date=4 October 2016|location=}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Sri Lanka}}&nbsp;\u2013 President [[Maithripala Sirisena]] called PM Modi to condemn the attack and offered condolences to the families of the victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PMOIndia/status/778224808345542658|title=PMO India on Twitter|work=Twitter|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> The Foreign Ministry issued a statement that read the attack and reaffirmed the \"urgent need for sustained\" regional and global cooperation to eliminate terrorism. \"In the hour of grief, the Government of Sri Lanka offers its condolences to the families of the victims of the attack.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/india/sri-lanka-condemns-terror-attack-in-kashmirs-uri_1931268.html|title=Sri Lanka condemns terror attack in Kashmir's Uri|work=Zee News|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> On 30 September, Sri Lanka postponed its participation for the SAARC summit, saying the prevailing environment in the region was not conducive.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/south-asia/now-sri-lanka-pulls-out-of-saarc-summit/article9168393.ece Another jolt to Pakistan as Sri Lanka pulls out of SAARC Summit], The Hindu, 1 October 2016</ref>\n* {{flag|South Korea}}&nbsp;\u2013 South Korea{{who|date=September 2016}} extended its \"deepest condolences and sympathy to the innocent victims of the terrorist attack and their bereaved families,\" adding that terrorism is an unjustifiable crime against humanity.<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Turkey}}&nbsp;\u2013 Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement expressing sorrow over the \"heinous attack,\" extending its condolences \"to the families of soldiers who lost their lives\" and wishing those injured a speedy recovery. The ministry said it was \"deeply concerned about the increasing tension and casualties occurring recently in Jammu and Kashmir,\" and expressed hope that problems would be \"settled through dialogue and within the framework of the relevant UN resolutions.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-229_-18-september-2016_-press-release-regarding-the-terrorist-attack-perpetrated-in-jammu-and-kashmir.en.mfa | title=No: 229, 18 September 2016, Press Release Regarding the Terrorist Attack Perpetrated in Jammu and Kashmir | work=Turkish Ministry of Foreign Affairs | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=20 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919132836/http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-229_-18-september-2016_-press-release-regarding-the-terrorist-attack-perpetrated-in-jammu-and-kashmir.en.mfa | archive-date=19 September 2016 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* {{flag|UAE}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation issued a statement \"renewing the nation's firm stand against terrorism in all its forms and manifestations, its solidarity with the Republic of India and its support to all actions it may take to confront and eradicate terrorism\". It further offered deepest condolences and sympathy to the families of the victims, as well as the government and people of India, and wished a speedy recovery to those who had been injured.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wam.ae/en/news/emirates-international/1395300099805.html | title=UAE condemns terrorist attack against Indian military base in Kashmir | work=Emirates News Agency | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=18 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918201320/http://www.wam.ae/en/news/emirates-international/1395300099805.html | archive-date=18 September 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* {{flag|United Kingdom}}&nbsp;\u2013 Foreign Secretary [[Boris Johnson]] condemned the attack. \"The UK strongly condemns this morning's terrorist attack in Indian-administered Kashmir. I offer my deepest condolences to the victims and their families and friends. The UK condemns all forms of terrorism, and stands shoulder to shoulder with India in the fight against terrorism, and in bringing the perpetrators to justice.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-press-release-foreign-secretary-condemns-attack-in-indian-administered-kashmir | title=FCO Press Release: Foreign Secretary condemns attack in Indian-administered Kashmir | work=Gov.uk | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|United States}}&nbsp;\u2013 State Department spokesperson [[John Kirby (admiral)|John Kirby]] said: \"The United States strongly condemns the terrorist attack on an Indian army base in Kashmir during the early morning of September 18. We extend our condolences to the victims and their families. The United States is committed to our strong partnership with the Indian government to combat terrorism.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2016/09/262053.htm | title=Indian Army Brigade Headquarters in Uri | work=U.S. Department of State | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n: The Chairman of the [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade|US House Subcommittee on Terrorism]], Congressman [[Ted Poe]] from Texas, along with [[Dana Rohrabacher]] from California, introduced a bill in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] calling for a declaration of Pakistan as a \"state sponsor of terrorism.\" The bill HR6069 requires the president to issue a report within 90 days detailing Pakistan's role in supporting international terrorism followed by discussion from the [[US Secretary of State]]. Ted Poe said in a statement that Pakistan was not only an untrustworthy ally but it has also aided and abetted the enemies of the United States. He called the Uri attack the \"latest consequence of Pakistan's longstanding irresponsible policy of supporting and providing operational space for '[[jihad]]i' terrorist groups\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1185650/us-lawmakers-move-bill-designate-pakistan-terrorist-state/|title=US lawmakers move bill to designate Pakistan a terrorist state|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref><ref>\n[http://poe.house.gov/2016/9/chairman-poe-introduces-the-pakistan-state-sponsor-of-terrorism-designation-act Chairman Poe introduces the Pakistan State Sponsor of Terrorism Designation Act], Press release, U. S. Congressman Ted Poe (official website), 20 September 2016.\n</ref>\n: {{flag|Venezuela}}&nbsp;\u2013 [[President of Venezuela|Venezuelan President]] [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] expressed solidarity with the people of India and stated: \"We are committed along with our brotherly people of the world to get into the depth of this problem that has generated proliferation of terrorist movements, which doesn't respect life and the need for coexistence of people.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/un-secretary-general-ban-ki-moon-condemns-uri-terror-attack/articleshow/54402038.cms | title=UN Secretary General Ban Ki-moon condemns Uri terror attack | work=Economic Times | date=19 September 2016 | accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Supranational bodies===\n* {{flag|EU}}&nbsp;\u2013 An EU spokesperson issued a statement calling for solidarity against non-state militancy and expressing condolences to the families of the victims of the attack. \"Yesterday's terrorist attack against the Uri Indian military camp demonstrates once again that terrorism has no boundaries, and that it is a global threat. As far as the European Union is concerned, we are committed to working with our partners and the international community at large to combat terrorism in all its forms. Our first thoughts and condolences go to the victims of this attack and to their families. We wish a quick recovery to those who were injured.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eeas.europa.eu/node/10040_en|title=Attack at the Indian Army Camp in Uri&nbsp;\u2013 eeas&nbsp;\u2013 European Commission|author=|date=|work=europa.eu}}</ref>\n* {{flag|UN}}&nbsp;\u2013 On 19 September, [[Ban Ki-moon]], the spokesperson of the [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]], issued a statement which condemned the attack and expressed his deepest sympathy and condolences to the families of the soldiers who lost their lives and to the government of India. He also wished a speedy recovery to those who were injured during the attack and hoped that the perpetrators of the army base will be identified and brought to justice.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-attack-un-secretary-general-ban-ki-moon-condemns-3038462/ | title=Uri terror attack: UN Secretary General Ban Ki-moon condemns act| work=The Indian Express | date=19 September 2016 | accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\nThe ''[[Deutsche Welle]]'' noted that Kashmir was already in international headlines at the time of the Uri attack due to the anti-India protests. It further noted that immediately after the attack, [[mainstream media]] in India and Pakistan engaged in \"angry\" rhetoric towards each other.<ref name=DWmedia>{{cite news|title=How Indian and Pakistani media are covering Kashmir unrest|url=http://www.dw.com/en/how-indian-and-pakistani-media-are-covering-kashmir-unrest/a-19562791}}</ref> A video of Indian soldiers chanting \"Pakistan, hear this loud and clear: If ... war breaks out you will be obliterated\" went viral. ''[[The Diplomat]]'' noted that many Indian media had openly called for a war on Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Could India and Pakistan Go to War?|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/09/could-india-and-pakistan-go-to-war/}}</ref>\n\n''[[India Today]]'' suggested that the fallout from the Uri attack would hurt Pakistani artists in India.<ref name=ITartist>{{cite news|title=Uri aftermath: Pakistan artists to be banned in India?|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/indo-pak-tension-break-cultural-ties/1/772653.html}}</ref> [[Maharashtra Navnirman Sena]] gave all Pakistani artists in India 48 hours to leave the country and warned that they would be \"hunted down\".<ref name=IndiaExpressArtists>{{cite news|title=Zee Entertainment Enterprises|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/All-Pakistani-artists-have-left-Mumbai-will-hunt-down-whoever-is-still-left-MNS/2016/09/25/article3629539.ece}}</ref> [[Subhash Chandra]] also said Pakistani artists should leave.<ref name=ITartist/> [[Zee Entertainment Enterprises|Zee TV]] considered terminating Pakistani shows. The Indian Motion Picture Producers Association (IMPPA) decided to ban all Pakistani actors, actresses and technicians in India till the situation returned to normal.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> However Bollywood artists were divided towards the ban with some justifying it while some questioning its benefits.<ref name=\"firstpost.com\"/>\n\nOn 18 September, the [[Times of India]] revealed that the army personnel recovered a map from the attackers which had markings in the [[Pashtun language]] and indicated a detailed plan of action. Four [[AK-47]] rifles and four [[grenade launcher|under barrel grenade launchers]] along with ammunition were also recovered. According to the Indian Army, some of the items had Pakistani markings.<ref name=web/> This was denied by the [[National Investigation Agency]].\n\n''[[The Diplomat]]'' noted that the timing of the attack coincided with the Pakistani Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]]'s visit to New York to address the [[United Nations General Assembly]] the following week.<ref name=Diplomat>\nShawn Snow, [http://thediplomat.com/2016/09/17-indian-soldiers-killed-in-kashmir-india-pakistan-tensions-heating-up/ 17 Indian Soldiers Killed in Kashmir: India-Pakistan Tensions Heating up], The Diplomat, 19 September 2016.\n</ref> ''[[The Diplomat]]'', in another article, said that the attack was \"designed\" to increase public pressure against the Modi government's engagement with Pakistan.<ref name=Panda/>\n\nIt also reported that there was specific intelligence input from the [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] two days earlier that an attack was being planned against army formations close to the LOC.<ref>\n[https://www.thequint.com/uri-attack/2016/09/21/uri-avenged-2-india-paras-special-forces-cross-loc-uri-sector-jammu-and-kashmir-pakistan-neutralise-20-terrorists Exclusive: Uri Avenged As Spl Forces Cross LoC, Kill 20 Terrorists, report Chandan Nandy], The Quint, 22 September 2016.\n</ref> The intelligence agency had said that three ''fidayeen'' squads were launched from [[Pakistan-administered Kashmir]]. One of them attacked Uri, another went to [[Poonch (town)|Poonch]] where it was engaged by the security forces, and the third is believed to be targeting Srinagar highway.<ref name=intel>\n[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-specific-intelligence-inputs-ib-alert-army-units/1/767204.html Uri attack: There was specific intelligence inputs; IB alerted army units on Thursday], India Today, 18 September 2016.\n</ref> The [[India Today Television]] mentioned that, according to unnamed intelligence sources, Pakistan was plotting a \"spectacular event\" ahead of Nawaz Sharif's speech to the UN General Assembly.<ref>\n[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/video/pakistan-nawaz-sharif-un-speech-intel-sources/1/767147.html Uri attack: Pakistan plots spectacular event ahead of Sharif's UN speech, report Intel sources], India Today Television, 19 September 2016.\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n* [[2016 Indian Line of Control strike]] (Indian retaliation to this attack)\n* [[List of terrorist incidents in India]]\n* [[Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir]]\n* [[India-Pakistan Relations]]\n*[[Uri: The Surgical Strike|Uri The surgical strike]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Amit Sharma. [http://dbvideos.bhaskar.com/trending/how-terrorists-attacked-uri-30412.html \"Complete Coverage: URI Attack In 2 Minute (SEPT. 18, 2016) 3:30 AM\"]\n\n{{Jammu and Kashmir topics}}\n{{Kashmir conflict}}\n{{Indo-Pakistani relations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uri attack}}\n[[Category:September 2016 crimes in Asia]]\n[[Category:Kashmir conflict]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2016]]\n[[Category:Uri, Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in India in 2016]]\n[[Category:Attacks on military installations]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expert needed|1=India|reason=The article has been vandalised on multiple occasions. The facts needs to be cross-checked with sources.|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| partof     = the [[Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| map = {{Location map | India Jammu and Kashmir#India\n| width = 300\n| lat_deg = 34\n| lat_min = 5\n| lat_sec = 10\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_deg = 74\n| lon_min = 2\n| lon_sec = 0\n| lon_dir = E\n}}\n| map_size    = \n| map_alt     = Location in Jammu and Kashmir, India\n| map_caption = Location in Jammu and Kashmir, India\n| location    = Near [[Uri, Jammu and Kashmir|Uri]], [[Baramulla district]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]], India\n| date        = 18 September 2016\n| time        = 5.30 am\n| timezone    = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| type        = [[insurgency]], [[guerrilla warfare]]\n| fatalities  = 23 (19 soldiers, 4 terrorists)<ref name=\"BSF_jawan\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-attack-odia-bsf-jawan-succumbs-to-injuries-death-toll-rises-to-19/|title=Uri attack: BSF jawan succumbs to injuries, death toll rises to 19|publisher=The Indian Express|date=25 September 2016|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"succumbed\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/one-more-soldier-succumbs-to-injuries-toll-rises-to-18-in-uri-attack-army/story-ebPHK9AVNZY98gIAR3X1XP.html|title=One more soldier succumbs to injuries, death toll rises to 18 in Uri attack|publisher=Hindustan Times|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n| injuries    = 19\u201330<ref name=\"TOI19\">[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Uri-terror-attack-Indian-Army-camp-attacked-in-Jammu-and-Kashmir-17-killed-19-injured/articleshow/54389451.cms Uri terror attack: 17 soldiers killed, 19 injured in strike on Army camp], ''Times of India'', 18 September 2016.</ref><ref name=\"list\">[http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-terror-attack-list-of-jawans-who-died-fighting-terrorists/ Uri terror attack: List of jawans who died fighting terrorists], ''The Indian Express'', 18 September 2016.</ref><ref name=\"attack\"/>\n| victims     = <!-- or | victimf      = -->\n| perps       = \n|weapons    = 4 [[AK-47|AK-47 rifles]], 4 [[Grenade launcher|under barrel grenade launchers]], 5 [[Grenade|hand grenades]], 9 [[40 mm grenade|UBGL grenades]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-uri-attack-pm-modi-calls-for-pak-to-be-isolated-diplomatically-army-says-india-will-respond-at-appropriate-time-2256896|title=Uri attack: PM Modi calls for Pak to be isolated diplomatically, Army says India will respond at appropriate time|author=DNA India|date=19 September 2016|work=dnaindia.com|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n|motive     =\n| dfens      = [[Indian Army]]\n* [[Para (Special Forces)|Indian Army 4 Para (Special Forces)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/live-terror-fidayeen-attack-at-armys-uri-brigade-in-baramulla-kashmir-breaking-3036911/|title=Uri aftermath LIVE: Infiltration bids have increased this year: Army|author=|date=18 September 2016|work=indianexpress.com }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Terrorist attacks in India (since 2001)}}\n\nThere was an attack by four heavily armed terrorists on 18 September 2016, near the town of [[Uri, Jammu and Kashmir|Uri]] in the then Indian administered state of [[Jammu and Kashmir]]. It was reported as \"the deadliest attack on security forces in Kashmir in two decades\".<ref name=\"uri\">{{cite news|title=Militants attack Indian army base in Kashmir 'killing 17'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-37399969|accessdate=18 September 2016|work=|agency=BBC News|date=18 September 2016|location=}}</ref>  The terrorist group [[Jaish-e-Mohammed]] was involved in the planning and execution of the attack.<ref name=\"susperps\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-attack-jaish-suspects-in-hand-evidence-shown-to-envoy-3053717/|title=Uri attack: Jaish-e-Muhammad suspects in hand, evidence shown to envoy|date=28 September 2016|work=indianexpress.com}}</ref> At the time of the attack, the [[Kashmir Valley]] region was a centre of [[2016 Kashmir unrest|unrest]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/09/18/asia/india-kashmir-attack/|title=Soldiers killed in army base attack in Indian territory of Kashmir|work=CNN|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=21 September 2016|quote=After a few years of relative calm in Indian-administered Kashmir -- largely considered one of the world's most tumultuous geopolitical flashpoints since the India-Pakistan partition -- the region has been gripped by unrest for more than two months.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/32651887/suspected-rebels-attack-major-indian-army-base-in-kashmir|title=India blames Pakistan militants for Kashmir attack which killed 17|work=Yahoo|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=21 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919132241/https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/32651887/suspected-rebels-attack-major-indian-army-base-in-kashmir/ |archive-date=19 September 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Further|Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir|2016 Kashmir unrest}}\nSince 2015, the militants had increasingly taken to high-profile ''[[fidayeen]]'' attacks against the Indian security forces: in July 2015, three gunmen [[2015 Gurdaspur attack|attacked]] a bus and police station in [[Gurdaspur]] and earlier in 2016, 4\u20136 gunmen [[2016 Pathankot attack|attacked]] the [[Pathankot Air Force Station]]. Indian authorities blamed  [[Jaish-e-Mohammad]] for the latter attack.<ref name=Panda>\nAnkit Panda, [http://thediplomat.com/2016/09/gurdaspur-pathankot-and-now-uri-what-are-indias-options/ Gurdaspur, Pathankot, and Now Uri: What Are India's Options?], The Diplomat, 19 September 2016.\n</ref>\n\nAlso, since 8 July 2016, the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir has been undergoing continuous unrest following the killing of [[Burhan Wani]], a militant leader popular with the youth in the state.<ref name=DW>{{cite news|title=Indian troops suffer deadly Kashmir ambush|url=http://www.dw.com/en/indian-troops-suffer-deadly-kashmir-ambush/a-19559690}}</ref><ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=17 Indian Soldiers Killed by Militants in Kashmir|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/19/world/asia/17-indian-soldiers-killed-by-militants-in-kashmir.html?_r=1|publisher=[[New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name =CBC>{{cite news|title=17 Indian soldiers, 4 militants killed in Kashmir attack|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/kashmir-attack-1.3767723}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Militants sneak into Indian army base and mow down sleeping soldiers in Kashmir, killing 17|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-india-kashmir-20160918-snap-story.html}}</ref> The killing sparked violent protests against the Indian government in the valley,<ref name= time>{{cite web|title=A Terrorist Attack in Kashmir Sparks Fears of a Military Conflict Between India and Pakistan|url=http://time.com/4498891/kashmir-uri-attack-india-pakistan-military-conflict/}}</ref><ref name =AlJazeera1>{{cite news |title=17 Indian soldiers killed in attack on Kashmir base|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/09/20-dead-attack-army-base-kashmir-160918055803596.html}}</ref> leading to the  protests being described as the \"largest anti-India protests\" against Indian rule in recent years.<ref name =CBC/><ref name=WP>{{cite news|title=17 soldiers killed in attack at Indian army base in Kashmir|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/suspected-militants-attack-indian-army-base-in-kashmir/2016/09/17/23674c1a-7d4a-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=More than a dozen Indian soldiers killed in Kashmir attack|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/more-than-a-dozen-indian-soldiers-killed-in-kashmir-attack/}}</ref>\n\n==Attack==\nAt around 5:30&nbsp;a.m. on 18 September, four militants attacked an [[Indian Army]] brigade headquarters in [[Uri, Jammu and Kashmir|Uri]], near the [[Line of Control]] in a pre-dawn ambush. They were said to have lobbed 17 grenades in three minutes. As a rear administrative base camp with tents caught fire, 17 army personnel were killed during the attack. An additional 19-30 soldiers were reported to have been injured. A gun battle ensued lasting six hours, during which all the four militants were killed.<ref name=\"TOI19\"/><ref name=\"attack\">{{cite news|title=Tents set on fire, troops shot while coming out|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/militants-attack-army-battalion-in-uri-tents-set-on-fire-troops-shot-while-coming-out/article9120925.ece?homepage=true|accessdate=18 September 2016|work=The Hindu|agency=|date=18 September 2016|location=}}\n</ref><ref name=IndiaToday>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-inside-story-pashtun-map-pakistani-ammunition-jash-e-mohammed/1/767345.html Uri attack: An inside story of how it happened], India Today, 18 September 2016.</ref><ref name=plan>\n[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/sequence-of-the-uri-attack-the-plan-of-the-terrorists/articleshow/54397873.cms Sequence of the Uri attack & the plan of the terrorists], The Economic Times, 19 September 2016.</ref><ref name=Quint/>\nCombing operations continued to flush out additional terrorists thought to be alive.<ref name=\"uri\"/>\n\nMost of the soldiers killed were from the 10th battalion, [[Dogra Regiment]] (10 Dogra) and 6th battalion, [[Bihar Regiment]] (6 Bihar).<ref name=Quint>[https://www.thequint.com/india/2016/09/18/militants-attack-army-headquarters-in-uri-kashmir-firing-ongoing Uri Attack: Most of the 17 Soldiers Died in a Tent Fire], The Quint, 19 September 2016.</ref> One of the injured soldiers succumbed to his injuries on 19 September at RR Hospital in [[New Delhi]], followed by another soldier on 24 September, bringing the death toll to 19.<ref name=\"BSF_jawan\"/><ref name=\"succumbed\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/uri-attack-death-toll-touches-18-india-decides-to-isolate-pakistan-on-the-global-stage-3011334.html|title=Uri attack: Death toll touches 18, India decides to isolate Pakistan on the global stage&nbsp;\u2013 Firstpost|date=2016-09-19|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-19}}</ref>\n\nThe casualties were primarily believed to have occurred as a result of non-[[fire retardant]] transition tents. This was the time of a troops shift, whereby troops from 6 Bihar were replacing troops from 10 Dogra. The incoming troops were housed in tents, which are normally avoided in sensitive areas around the [[Line of Control|LoC]] like Uri. The attackers snuck into the camp breaching heavy security and seemed to know exactly where to strike. Seven of the personnel killed were support staff, including cooks and barbers.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/high-casualties-due-to-transition-tents/article9121325.ece High casualties due to transition tents], The Hindu, 19 September 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/uri-base-caught-off-guard-despite-specific-intel-army-investigates-1461701 Uri Base Caught Off-Guard Despite Specific Intel? Army Investigates], NDTV News, 20 September 2016.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nOn 19 September, Home Minister [[Rajnath Singh]], Defense Minister [[Manohar Parrikar]], [[Chief of the Army Staff (India)|Chief of the Army Staff]] [[Dalbir Singh]], National Security Advisor [[Ajit Doval]] and other officials of the Home and Defence ministries met to review the security situation in Kashmir, particularly in areas along the Line of Control.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-attack-rajnath-singh-manohar-parrikar-nsa-army-chief-meet-to-discuss-kashmir-3038767/|title=Uri attack: Rajnath Singh, Manohar Parrikar, NSA, Army chief meet to discuss Kashmir|agency=Press Trust of India|publisher=The Indian Express|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> The [[National Investigation Agency]] filed a [[first information report]] regarding the attack and took over the investigation from [[Jammu and Kashmir Police]] on 20 September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Uri-terror-attack-NIA-files-FIR-begins-probe/articleshow/54424217.cms|title=Uri terror attack: NIA files FIR, begins probe|publisher=Times of India|date=20 September 2016|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Pakistan International Airlines]] cancelled flights to some parts of Kashmir on 21 September in the aftermath of the attack.<ref>{{cite news|title=PIA cancels flights to Northern areas due to airspace restrictions|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1185715/pia-cancels-flights-northern-areas-due-air-space-restrictions/|publisher=[[The Express Tribune]]}}</ref> Security around the army installation in Uri was intensified following the attack, while soldiers on both the Indian and Pakistani side of Line of Control were placed on high alert.<ref>{{cite news|title=Troops on high alert along LoC|url=http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/troops-high-alert-along-loc/|publisher=[[Daily Excelsior]]|date=22 September 2016|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Postponement of SAARC summit===\nIn the wake of the attack, India cancelled its participation in the [[19th SAARC summit]] to be held in November in [[Islamabad]], Pakistan. The Ministry of External Affairs issued a statement, saying, \"India has conveyed to current SAARC Chair Nepal that increasing cross-border terrorist attacks in the region and growing interference in the internal affairs of Member States by one country have created an environment that is not conducive to the successful holding of the 19th SAARC Summit in Islamabad in November 2016.\" \"In the prevailing circumstances, the Government of India is unable to participate in the proposed Summit in Islamabad\", the statement said.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/india-pulls-out-of-saarc-summit-in-islamabad-1467221|title=PM Narendra Modi Will Not Attend SAARC Summit In Pakistan|work=ndtv.com}}</ref>\n\nOn India withdrawing from the scheduled SAARC summit in Islamabad, Pakistan's Foreign Office termed the withdrawal \"unfortunate\", and posted a rejoinder stating: \"As for the excuse used by India, the world knows that it is India that has been perpetrating and financing terrorism in Pakistan.\" The statement included a reference to Indian national [[Kulbhushan Jadhav]], detained by Pakistan for espionage, and accused India of violating international laws by interfering inside Pakistan.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1189456/india-pulls-saarc-summit-islamabad/|title=India pulls out of SAARC summit in Islamabad|date=27 September 2016|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nLater, Afghanistan, Bangladesh and Bhutan also withdrew from the summit.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/dhaka-kabul-thimphu-too-blame-islamabad-saarc-summit-to-be-called-off-3054953/ | title=SAARC summit to be called off as Dhaka, Kabul and Thimphu too slam Islamabad | work=The Indian Express | date=29 September 2016 | accessdate=24 September 2016 | author=Roy, Shubhajit | location=New Delhi}}</ref><ref name = \"HT\">{{cite web|title=SAARC summit collapses after India and three other members pull out|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/saarc-summit-collapses-after-india-and-3-other-members-pull-out/story-kIMWfSqirGLzB6MEfuS3CN.html|website=Hindustan Times|accessdate=29 September 2016|date=28 September 2016}}</ref> On 30 September 2016,  Pakistan stated that the summit scheduled for 9 and 10 November in Islamabad would be held on an alternative date.<ref>{{cite web|title=SAARC summit 'postponed indefinitely'|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/saarc-summit-postponed-indefinitely/article9170272.ece|work=The Hindu|date=1 October 2016|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Indian retaliation===\n{{See also|2016 Indian Line of Control strike}}\nOn 28 September, eleven days after the attack, the Indian Army conducted retaliatory \"surgical strikes\" on what it termed \"launch-pads\" used by militants in [[Pakistan administered Kashmir]].<ref name=Economist>[https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21708302-there-still-more-smoke-fire-heated-exchanges-how-long-reversing-roles?zid=306&ah=1b164dbd43b0cb27ba0d4c3b12a5e227 India and Pakistan: Reversing roles], The Economist, 8 October 2016.</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Jamal |first=Umair |title=India Pakistan Conflict: what is next for the historic foes? |publisher=Al Jazeera Centre for Studies |date=17 November 2016 |url=http://studies.aljazeera.net/mritems/Documents/2016/11/17/fa613052c2b84f21a192cb060ef4601d_100.pdf |p=3}}</ref> Indian Director General of Military Operations (DGMO) Lt Gen Ranbir Singh said that it had made a preemptive strike against \"terrorist teams\" who were preparing to \"carry out infiltration and conduct terrorist strikes inside Jammu and Kashmir and in various metros in other states\".<ref name=BBC2>{{cite web|title=Kashmir attack: India 'launches strikes against militants'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37504308|website=BBC News|accessdate=29 September 2016|date=29 September 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' while citing Indian reports, reported that Indian commandos crossed the Line of Control and struck at the safe houses, allegedly killing approximately 150 pakistan sponsored terrorists.<ref name=Economist/> Pakistani officials on  next day did press conference with National and International media on the site. They rejected Indian claims and asserted that Indian Army never crossed the Line of Control.\n\n===Bilateral boycott===\nFollowing the uproar after the Uri attack, Indian Motion Picture Producers Association (IMPPA) decided to ban all Pakistani actors, actresses and technicians working in India till the situation returns to normal.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/imppa-passes-resolution-temporarily-ban-pakistani-artists-india-twitter-reacts-695956|title=IMPPA passes resolution to temporarily ban Pakistani artists in India; Twitter reacts|first=Suparno|last=Sarkar|work=ibtimes.co.in}}</ref> Bollywood artists were divided towards the ban with some justifying it while some questioning its benefits.<ref name=\"firstpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/salman-khan-nana-patekar-ranbir-kapoor-heres-what-bollywood-said-on-pak-actors-ban-3031294.html|title=Salman Khan, Nana Patekar, Ranbir Kapoor: Here's what Bollywood said on Pak actors ban - Firstpost|date=3 October 2016|work=firstpost.com}}</ref> Indian TV entertainment channel ''[[Zindagi (TV channel)|Zindagi]]'' announced discontinuation of airing Pakistani TV shows on the channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/after-pak-show-ban-zindagi-channel-to-view-indian-television-content-3063351/|title=After Pak Show ban, Zindagi Channel to bank on Indian, Turkish content|date=3 October 2016|work=indianexpress.com}}</ref> The Pakistani government responded in October with a blanket ban on all Indian television and radio programming in Pakistan.<ref name=\"bans_Indian\">{{cite news|title=Pakistan bans all Indian TV and radio as tensions mount|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37731089|accessdate=21 October 2016|work=|agency=BBC News|date=21 October 2016|location=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI), the national governing body for cricket in India, ruled out the possibility of reviving bilateral cricket ties with Pakistan in the near future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/bcci-chief-anurag-thakur-says-no-question-of-playing-cricket-with-pakistan-after-uri-attack-3018372.html|title=Uri attack aftermath: BCCI chief Anurag Thakur says no question of playing cricket with Pakistan - Firstpost|date=23 September 2016|work=firstpost.com}}</ref> BCCI also asked the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) to not group Indian and Pakistan cricket teams together in international tournaments, keeping in mind border tensions between the two countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/news/india-pakistan-shouldnt-be-grouped-together-in-international-events-bcci-to-icc-cricket-1468631|title=India, Pakistan Shouldn't be Grouped Together in International Events: BCCI to ICC \u2013 NDTV Sports|first=|last=NDTVSports.com|work=ndtv.com}}</ref> [[Badminton Association of India]], the governing body for badminton in India, decided to boycott the Pakistan International Series scheduled to be held in Islamabad in October, as an act of \"solidarity\" with the government's diplomatic offensive against Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/other-sports/indian-badminton-association-boycotts-series-in-pakistan/story-yNlpCUO4kTGqHNrQqLOVLI.html|title=Indian badminton association boycotts series in Pakistan|date=2 October 2016|work=hindustantimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n\nAn initial investigation into the attack indicated that there were several procedural lapses at the camp. According to the standard security procedures, any tall grass and bushes around vital security installations should be trimmed. However, this procedure was not followed by the Uri camp which might have allowed terrorists to sneak into the camp undetected using the tall grass and bushes around the perimeter. In addition, the probe also indicated that two manned guard posts failed to detect the intrusion because the coordination between them might have been poor. It also indicated that the terrorists had infiltrated the Indian territory through [[Haji Pir Pass]] on the intervening night of 16\u201317 September and stayed in Sukhdar village which is located at a vantage point that allows an unhindered view of the layout of the camp as well as movement of the personnel in it.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Uri-terror-attack-Many-procedural-lapses-at-Army-camp-says-initial-probe/articleshow/54466648.cms| title=Uri terror attack: Many procedural lapses at Army camp, says initial probe], Times of India, 22 September 2016.}}</ref>\n\n===Perpetrators===\nThe Director General of military operations, Lieutenant-General Ranbir Singh, said that there was evidence{{clarify|date=December 2017}}{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} that the attackers belonged to [[Jaish-e-Mohammad]].<ref name=\"congressional\">{{Cite journal| last = Cronin| first = Audrey Kurth|author2=Huda Aden |author3=Adam Frost |author4=Benjamin Jones | title = Foreign Terrorist Organizations| journal = CRS Report for Congress| volume = | issue = | pages= 40\u201343  | publisher = Congressional Research Service| location = Washington, D.C.| date = 2004-02-06| url = https://fas.org/irp/crs/RL32223.pdf| accessdate = 2009-12-02}}</ref> He established a hotline contact with his Pakistani counterpart and conveyed India's serious concern on the issue.<ref name=IndiaToday/><ref name=web>[http://www.timesofindia.com/india/Jaish-terrorists-behind-Uri-attack-had-items-with-Pakistani-markings-Army/articleshow/54392506.cms Jaish terrorists behind Uri attack, had items with Pakistani markings: Army], Times Of India, 18 September 2016.</ref> Singh also stated that the militants used [[incendiary ammunition]] to set fire to the tents.<ref name=IndiaToday/><ref name=\"NIA begins\">[http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/uri-attack-nia-team-begins-probe-visits-encounter-site/article9125398.ece NIA team begins probe, visits Uri encounter site], The Hindu, 20 September 2016.</ref>\n\nThe Indian Ministry of External Affairs said:\n\n{{quote|In the recent incidents, we have recovered a number of items that include GPS from the bodies of terrorists with coordinates that indicate the point and time of infiltration across the LoC and the subsequent route to the terror attack site; grenades with Pakistani markings; communication matrix sheets; communication equipment; and other stores made in Pakistan, including food, medicines and clothes.<ref name=envoy/>}}\n\nWhilst, on 29 September, National Investigation Agency officials said:\n\n{{Quote|text=Until now, little hard evidence has emerged to link the perpetrators of the terror attack in Uri to specific jihadist groups in Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-terror-attack-soldiers-dead-nia-probe-results-pakistan-lashkar-planned-3041576/|title=Uri attack probe: Terrorists locked soldiers in cook house, store|date=2016-09-21|newspaper=The Indian Express|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n}}\n\nFormer Pakistani General [[Pervez Musharraf]] said the weapons that India reported as used by militants, and reported to have Pakistani markings, could be procured anywhere in the world, not just in Pakistan.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|title=Pervez Musharraf blasts on \"double standards\" of India on terrorism|url=http://channel24.pk/breaking-news/2016/09/21/pervez-musharraf-blasts-india-terrorism/}}</ref> Musharraf further said since many American weapons had inadvertently fallen into the hands of the [[Taliban]], it is possible for Pakistani weapons to have been acquired by the perpetrators without Pakistani involvement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Uri attack: Pervez Musharraf denies terrorists used Pakistani weapons|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-pervez-musharraf-denies-terrorists-used-pakistani-weapons/1/769404.html}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September, the Indian Army said that two Pakistani nationals{{efn|The two individuals were identified as Ahasan Kursheed of [[Khaliana Kalan]]{{coord|34|4|30|N|73|53|10|E|name=Khaliana Kalan|display=none}} and Faisal Hussain Awan of [[Potha Bainsi|Potha Jahangir]]{{coord|33|7|51|N|73|52|31|E|name=Potha|display=none}}.}} from [[Pakistan administered Kashmir]] were arrested by the [[Border Security Force]] in the Uri sector. They were said to have been recruited by Jaish-e-Mohammad two years ago for the purpose of acting as guides to infiltrating groups in the Uri sector. These guides themselves did not have a role in the Uri attack. They were being questioned for gathering intelligence about infiltration attempts.<ref>\n[http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-attack-two-jem-guides-from-pok-arrested-army-3048685/ Two JeM \u2018guides\u2019 arrested in Uri: Army], The Indian Express, 25 September 2016.</ref> Pakistan denied these allegations.<ref name=\"SSA\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1286447/|title=Two guides from Muzaffarabad facilitated Uri attackers, India tells Pakistan|work=Dawn|first=Syed Sammer|last=Abbas|date=27 September 2016|accessdate=28 September 2016|quote=Pakistan on Tuesday promptly rejected Indian allegations of its involvement in the Uri army base attack, soon after Indian authorities said they had shared \"evidence\" with Pakistan High Commissioner to New Delhi Abdul Basit.}}</ref> On 26 February 2017, India's National Investigative Agency (NIA) decided to file a closure report after failing to find any evidence against the two men whom they accused of facilitating the Uri army base attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1339596/india-fails-substantiate-claim-pakistans-involvement-uri-attack/|title=India fails to substantiate claim of Pakistan's involvement in Uri attack - The Express Tribune|date=26 February 2017|publisher=|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 October 2016, the Indian media reported that street \"posters\" in [[Gujranwala]], Pakistan, attributed to [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] (LeT) claimed responsibility for the Uri attack.<ref name=\"respperp\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/exclusive-uri-attack-in-posters-pasted-on-gujaranwala-streets-lashkar-claims-responsibility-3101738/|title=In posters pasted on Gujranwala streets, Lashkar claims responsibility of Uri Attack|date=25 October 2016|newspaper=The Indian Express}}</ref><ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-let-terror-hafiz-saeed-pakistan/1/794879.html Posters in Pakistan town show Lashkar claiming responsibility for Uri attack], India Today, 25 October 2016.</ref> The posters claimed that one of LeT's fighters Mohammad Anas, code-named Abu Saraqa, died in the Uri attack, and there would be a funeral prayer followed by a speech by the LeT chief [[Hafiz Muhammad Saeed|Hafiz Saeed]] on 25 October. The poster also claimed death of 177 Indian soldiers in Uri attack. After the images of the poster circulated on the Internet, the organisation claimed that it was a hoax. [[Abbas Nasir]], the former editor of ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]'', confirmed the report about the posters on Twitter but stated that the funeral prayers have been postponed.<ref name=confirm>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Lashkar-claims-responsibility-for-Uri-terror-attack/articleshowprint/55047490.cms?null Lashkar-e-Taiba claims responsibility for Uri terror attack], The Times of India, 25 October 2016.</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n\n===India===\nPrime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and members of his cabinet condemned the attack.<ref name=\"uri\"/> Minister of Defence Manohar Parrikar and Indian Army chief General Dalbir Singh visited [[Kashmir valley|Kashmir]] soon after the attack to assess the ongoing military operations and review the security situation in the region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/parrikar-army-chief-visit-kashmir-review-security/|title=Parrikar, Army chief visit Kashmir, review security|publisher=Daily Excelsior|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Parrikar instructed the army to take firm action against those responsible for the attack and also stated that the deaths of the soldiers \"will not go in vain.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/after-uri-attack-manohar-parrikar-instructs-army-to-take-firm-action-1460286|title=After Uri Attack, Manohar Parrikar Instructs Army To Take 'Firm Action'|publisher=Daily Excelsior|date=18 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Home Minister Rajnath Singh accused Pakistan of what he called its \"continued and direct support to terrorism and terrorist groups,\" calling Pakistan a \"terrorist state\" that should be \"isolated.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/isolate-terrorist-state-pakistan-says-rajnath-singh-after-kashmir-attack-1460127|title=Isolate 'Terrorist State' Pakistan, Says Rajnath Singh After Kashmir Attack|work=ndtv.com}}</ref> Minister of State for Defence Subhash Bhamre stated that the \"entire nation was traumatised\" over the death of the soldiers and was \"united in this hour of grief.\" He also stated that the Prime Minister, Home Minister and Defence Minister had come to a conclusion that some sort of a \"response\" needs to be given to Pakistan.<ref name=\"Bhamre\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/uri-terror-attack-mos-defence-bhamre-confirms-death-toll-still-17/story-XdSsKIzLVLxzm1tCOM1GwO.html |title=MoS defence denies reports of 3 more Uri attack deaths |publisher=Hindustan Times |date=19 September 2016 |accessdate=19 September 2016}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Minister of State for External Affairs]] [[Sushma Swaraj]] and former Army chief [[Vijay Kumar Singh]] stated that India will give a \"befitting reply\" to the attack. He called upon the Indian Armed Forces to scale up their security and described a cold and calculated response as the need of the hour. He also called for an investigation into the shortcomings which led to the attack while stating that the Army should decide its response \"coolly\" with proper planning.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/india-will-give-a-cold-calculated-and-befitting-reply-says-general-vk-singh-on-uri-attack/381581/|title=India will give a cold, calculated, and befitting reply, says General VK Singh on Uri attack|publisher=The Financial Express|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/VK-Singh-calls-for-probe-into-lacunas-which-led-to-Uri-attack/articleshow/54405818.cms|title=VK Singh calls for probe into lacunas which led to Uri attack|agency=Press Trust of India|publisher=Times of India|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Many{{vague|date=September 2016}} Indian politicians and public figures have condemned the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Uri-terror-attack-Demands-rise-for-befitting-reply-to-Pakistan/articleshow/54404645.cms|title=Uri terror attack: Demands rise for 'befitting reply' to Pakistan|first=Shailaja|last=Neelakantan|publisher=Times of India|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Former Indian diplomats and foreign policy experts{{who|date=September 2016}} have said that India had been driven to the wall and that a measured and effective response was needed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/uri-attack-india-driven-to-the-wall-say-diplomats/article9121284.ece|title=Uri attack: India driven to the wall, say diplomats|work=The Hindu|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref> The opposition [[Indian National Congress]] has said that there was no more scope for constructive dialogue with Pakistan.<ref>[http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/no-scope-for-constructive-dialogue-with-pak-post-uri-attack-congress-116091900885_1.html No scope for constructive dialogue with Pak post-Uri attack: Congress], Business Standard, 19 September 2016.\n</ref>\n\nLater on the same day, India called upon the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] to urge Pakistan to put an end to cross-border infiltration and dismantle the non-state militant infrastructure since the likes of [[Hafeez Saeed]] (the chief of [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]]) and [[Syed Salahuddin]] (the chief of [[Hizbul Mujahideen]]) can hold huge rallies in Pakistan's main cities. It suggested that active support for such groups has become the \"new normal\" in Pakistan. It claimed that \"zero tolerance\" to non-state militancy was an international obligation.<ref>[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/active-support-for-terrorists-like-hafiz-saeed-syed-salahuddin-new-normal-in-pakistan-india-at-un-human-rights-council/articleshow/54416144.cms Active support for terrorists like Hafiz Saeed, Syed Salahuddin new normal in Pakistan: India at UN Human Rights Council], The Economic Times, 20 September 2016.</ref> The Indian government summoned the Pakistani envoy and handed him a dossier that alleged Pakistani involvement as well as a warning that Pakistan needs to rein in militants they say operate from Pakistan.<ref name=envoy>[http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/days-after-uri-attack-india-summons-pakistan-envoy-abdul-basit-1464745 3 Days After Uri Attack, India Hands Pakistan Envoy Evidence And A Warning], NDTV News, 21 September 2016.</ref>\n\nOn 24 September, Prime Minister Modi formally responded to the attack during a BJP rally in Kozhikode, Kerala; in his address, he charged Pakistan with responsibility for the attack, saying that India would \"never forget\" Uri and would \"leave no stone unturned to isolate Pakistan in the world.\" He called upon the citizens of both India and Pakistan to fight against poverty. \"I want to say that India is ready for a war... India is ready for a war on poverty. Let both countries fight to see who would eradicate poverty first... I want to tell the youth of Pakistan, let's have a war on ending unemployment... I want to call out to the children in Pakistan, let's declare war on illiteracy. Let's see who wins.\"<ref name=\"Kozhikode\">{{cite news|title=PM Modi speaks to people of Pakistan: Let us go to war against poverty, unemployment... let's see who wins|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/pm-narendra-modi-speaks-to-the-people-of-pakistan-lets-go-to-war-against-poverty-unemployment-lets-see-who-wins-3048329/|accessdate=27 September 2016|work=|agency=The Indian Express|date=25 September 2016|location=}}</ref>\n\nIn further responding to the attack, on 26 September, the Indian government stated it would exercise its rights under the 1960 [[Indus Waters Treaty]] to the full and would expand its utilisation of its rivers flowing through Jammu and Kashmir. Talks under the aegis of the Permanent Indus Commission, to which any disputes may be submitted, would cease \"until terror comes to an end.\" The body had most recently met in July 2016.<ref name=\"suspend_Indus\">{{cite news|title=India suspends talks on Indus water pact|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-likely-to-suspend-indus-water-commission-talks/article9150223.ece|accessdate=27 September 2016|work=|agency=The Hindu|date=26 September 2016|location=}}</ref> The government subsequently stated it would review Pakistan's most-favoured-nation (MFN) trade status, which India had granted in 1996.<ref name=\"MFN\">{{cite news|title=India to review MFN status to Pakistan on Thursday|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-to-review-pakistans-mfn-status-on-thursday/article9153752.ece?homepage=true|accessdate=27 September 2016|work=|agency=The Hindu|date=27 September 2016|location=}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan===\nPakistan's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Pakistan)|Foreign Ministry]] rejected India's allegations of involvement in the attack. The ministry asserted that India had a \"tendency\" of accusing Pakistan for incidents inside its territory, adding that \"in the past many Indians were involved in the terrorist acts for which India had blamed Pakistan.\"<ref name=Dawn/> The ministry deemed Indian statements as \"vitriolic.\"<ref name =BBC3>{{cite news|title=Kashmir attack: Pakistan hits back at India accusations|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37405719|accessdate=19 September 2016|work=|agency=BBC News|date=19 September 2016|location=}}</ref> Pakistan's foreign ministry also accused the Indian government of trying to deflect attention from the [[Human rights abuses in Jammu and Kashmir|human rights situation in Kashmir]], with a reference to the [[2016 Kashmir unrest|ongoing civil unrest]]. It said the situation in Indian-administered Kashmir was \"not of Pakistan's making but a direct consequence of illegal Indian occupation and a long history of atrocities\", and that India's reaction of accusing Pakistan without investigations was \"deplorable.\"<ref name =BBC3/>\n\nDuring a press conference in [[London]], Pakistani Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] linked the incident to the recent unrest and human rights issues in Kashmir.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/uri-attack-could-be-a-reaction-to-situation-in-kashmir-sharif/article9142318.ece|title=Uri attack could be a 'reaction' to situation in Kashmir, says Sharif|work=The Hindu|date=24 September 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> Interior Minister [[Nisar Ali Khan]] said there were several contradictions within [[Indian media]] reports over the evidence, and claimed India was imposing censorship when their \"lies were exposed.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1187406/run-govt-bring-brahamdagh-back-interpol/|title=Govt to bring Brahamdagh back through Interpol|work=The Express Tribune|date=24 September 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://aaj.tv/2016/09/india-has-no-evidence-nisar/|title=India has no evidence: Nisar|work=AAJ News|date=24 September 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> Defence Minister [[Khawaja Muhammad Asif]] termed the attack an \"inside job\", saying that no proof was provided substantiating India's allegations, and said India was not serious about solving the Kashmir dispute.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1286423/|title=Uri attack an inside job, says Khawaja Asif|work=Dawn|first=Adil Aziz|last=Khanzada|date=27 September 2016|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/india-staged-uri-attacks-says-pakistan-defence-minister-khawaja-asif-695528|title=India staged Uri attacks, says Pakistan Defence Minister Khawaja Asif|work=International Business Times|date=27 September 2016|accessdate=28 September 2016|first=Mangala|last=Dilip}}</ref> Pakistan's envoy in New Delhi, [[Abdul Basit (diplomat)|Abdul Basit]], told India's Foreign Secretary [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar|S. Jaishankar]] that India sought to divert world attention from state atrocities in Kashmir by blaming the attack on Pakistan. Basit also added that if India was serious about the investigations, it should not avoid allowing independent investigators to probe it.<ref name=\"SSA\"/>\n\nIn the hours following the attack, Pakistan's military established a [[hotline]] with the Indian military. The Pakistani military rejected Indian accusations, saying that infiltration was not possible across the heavily guarded LOC. Pakistan's Director General of Military Operations also asked the Indian military to provide actionable intelligence.<ref name=Dawn>{{cite news|title=Pakistan rejects India's allegations of involvement in terrorist attack in held Kashmir|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1284555|publisher=[[Dawn News]]}}</ref>\n\nPakistan's [[Chief of Army Staff (Pakistan)|Chief of Army Staff]] [[Raheel Sharif]] claimed that India was propagating a \"hostile narrative\" in response the attack and also stated that the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistani armed forces]] were \"prepared to respond to the entire spectrum of direct and indirect threat.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=India propagating 'hostile narrative' about Uri attack: Pak Army chief|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/india-propagating-hostile-narrative-about-uri-attack-pak-army-chief/story-LFHNi2z8BFDPow4xtjMGSM.html|accessdate=19 September 2016|work=Hindustan Times|date=19 September 2016|location=}}</ref>\n\nIn response to India's suspension of cooperation over the Indus Waters Treaty, [[Sartaj Aziz]] said India could not revoke the treaty unilaterally as per the IWT's provisions and international laws, and said such a move would be taken as an act of \"war and hostilities.\" Aziz said Pakistan would approach the United Nations Security Council in that event.<ref>[http://gulfnews.com/news/asia/pakistan/violation-of-water-treaty-risks-war-senior-pakistan-official-warns-1.1903026 Violation of water treaty risks war, senior Pakistan official warns], Gulf News, 28 September 2016</ref>\n\nOn India withdrawing from the scheduled SAARC summit in Islamabad, Pakistan's Foreign Office termed the withdrawal \"unfortunate\" and posted a rejoinder stating: \"As for the excuse used by India, the world knows that it is India that has been perpetrating and financing terrorism in Pakistan.\" The statement included a reference to Indian national [[Kulbhushan Yadav]], detained by Pakistan for espionage, and accused India of violating international laws by interfering inside Pakistan.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Other states===\n* {{flag|Afghanistan}}&nbsp;\u2013 [[Afghan Ambassador to India]] [[Shaida Mohammad Abdali]] condemned the attack. Pledging his nation's support to Prime Minister Narendra Modi's call for a strong and firm action against the perpetrators, Ambassador Abdali said: \"We fully support PM Modi's call for strong and firm action against those who terrorise people, and those who use terrorism as an instrument of foreign policy; seeing this for many years. Whoever uses terrorism shouldn't only be isolated but also held accountable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/uri-attack-afghan-envoy-calls-for-joint-strategy-to-fight-terrorist-groups-116091901080_1.html|title=Uri attack: Afghan envoy calls for joint strategy to fight terrorist groups|first=|last=ANI|date=19 September 2016|publisher=|via=Business Standard}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Armenia}}&nbsp;\u2013 Armenia condemned the attack and expressed condolences to \"families of killed and friendly people of India\".<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Bahrain}}&nbsp;\u2013 Bahrain's Ministry of Foreign Affairs affirmed the nation's \"full support to the friendly Republic of India in their actions to counter terrorism\" and called for \"concerted efforts to eliminate it (terrorism) and cut off its funding.\"<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Bangladesh}}&nbsp;\u2013Bangladesh High Commissioner to India Syed Muazzem Ali <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofa.gov.bd/foreign-secretary/mr-syed-muazzem-ali|title=Mr. Syed Muazzem Ali {{!}} Welcome to MOFA Website|website=www.mofa.gov.bd|access-date=2016-09-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927021916/http://www.mofa.gov.bd/foreign-secretary/mr-syed-muazzem-ali|archive-date=27 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> condemned the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/uri-terror-attack-bangladesh-stands-with-india-says-envoy-1293717.html|title=Uri Terror Attack: Bangladesh Stands With India, Says Envoy|date=19 September 2016|author=|work=news18.com}}</ref> Bangladesh&nbsp;\u2013 MOFA has not yet released a press release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofa.gov.bd/media/press-release|title=Press Release {{!}} Welcome to MOFA Website|website=www.mofa.gov.bd|access-date=2016-09-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912232224/http://mailto:mission.agartala@mofa.gov.bd/media/press-release|archive-date=12 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The country has also withdrawn from the 19th [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation|SAARC]] summit scheduled to be held in Islamabad, Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/india-pulls-out-of-saarc-meet-as-it-looks-to-isolate-pakistan-diplomatically-after-uri-terror-attack-262520.html|title=India Pulls Out Of SAARC, Bangladesh & Afghanistan Follow. Pak Heads Towards Total Isolation|access-date=2016-09-29}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Bhutan}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Foreign Ministry issued a statement that read: \"Bhutan strongly condemns terrorism in all its forms and stands with India in the fight against terrorism. Such heinous acts of terrorism calls for the need to step up international cooperation to combat the scourge of terrorism that poses a severe threat to the peace and stability of all countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/world/bhutan-condemns-uri-attack_1931286.html|title=Bhutan condemns Uri attack|work=Zee News|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Canada}}&nbsp;\u2013 Acting High Commissioner Jess Dutton issued a statement condemning the attack and extending Canada's condolences to the victims and their families. \"We are appalled by these attacks and stand with the Government of India in the fight against terrorism.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/india-inde/highlights-faits/2016/2016-09-19_Canada-condemns-attack_condamne-attaque_Uri.aspx?lang=en | title=Canada condemns attack on Indian Army camp at Uri | work=Government of Canada: Canada in India | date=19 September 2016 | accessdate=20 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218192746/http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/india-inde/highlights-faits/2016/2016-09-19_Canada-condemns-attack_condamne-attaque_Uri.aspx?lang=en | archive-date=18 December 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* {{flag|China}}&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Foreign Ministry]] issued a statement condemning the attack and expressed sympathy towards the families of the slain soldiers as well as the injured soldiers. It also expressed concerns about rising tensions in the Kashmir region and called upon India and Pakistan to hold dialogue and consultations in order to solve their differences and counter-terrorism operations.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-china-pakistan-india/1/767962.html | title=China condemns Uri attack, but wants India, Pakistan to have 'dialogue'| work=India Today | first=Ananth |last=Krishnan |date= 19 September 2016 |accessdate= 19 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|France}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Development issued a statement condemning the attack and calling for a peaceful settlement to disputes in Kashmir. \"France condemns in the firmest terms the terrible terrorist attack committed on 18 September against an Indian Army camp in the Kashmir region. It expresses its condolences to the families of the 17 Indian soldiers killed in this attack. France stands beside India in the struggle against terrorism. It calls on each state to effectively fight against terrorist groups operating on its territory or from its territory against other countries. France reaffirms its commitment for a peaceful and structured settlement of differences in the region of Kashmir.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/dossiers-pays/inde/http-publication-diplomatie-gouv-fr-fr-dossiers-pays-inde-evenements/article/inde-attaque-terroriste-18-09-16 | title=Inde&nbsp;\u2013 Attaque terrorist (18 September 2016) (fr) | work=France&nbsp;\u2013 Diplomacy | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref> France also called for \"decisive actions\" against anti-India terrorist organisations, including [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]], [[Jaish-e-Mohammed]] and [[Hizbul Mujahideen]].<ref name=\"toi-21sep\">{{cite news|title=Condemning Uri terror attack, France, Russia score direct hits against Pakistan|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Condemning-Uri-terror-attack-France-Russia-score-direct-hits-against-Pakistan/articleshow/54429098.cms|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=The Times of India|date=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Germany}}&nbsp;\u2013 Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]] condemned the attack and said, \"our thoughts are with the families of the murdered soldiers and with the many people who have been injured, some seriously.\"<ref name=\"FE\">{{cite news|title=Uri terror attack: After Russia, now Germany and Japan stand with India; condemn terrorist strike|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/uri-terror-attack-after-russia-now-germany-and-japan-stand-with-india-condemn-terrorist-strike/383379/|accessdate=20 September 2016|date=20 September 2016|work=The Financial Express}}</ref> He added, \"Germany stands resolutely at India's side in the fight against terrorism. At the Indo-German counterterrorism consultations, which will take place in a few days' time, we will further discuss the threats to our two countries' societies.\".<ref name=\"FE\"/>\n* {{flag|Italy}}&nbsp;\u2013 Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Paolo Gentiloni]] condemned the attack \"in Indian-administered Kashmir.\" He offered \"deepest condolences to the families of the victims and to the Indian authorities,\" also affirming \"Italy's solidarity with India in a common fight against terrorism to promote peace and security in the world.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.esteri.it/mae/en/sala_stampa/archivionotizie/comunicati/2016/09/l-italia-condanna-l-attacco-terroristico.html | title=Italy condemns Kashmir terror attack. Minister Gentiloni offers his condolences | work=Farnesina (Ministry of Foreign Affairs and External Cooperation) | date=19 September 2016 | accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Japan}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement which read: \"The Government of Japan strongly condemns the terrorist attack on the Indian Base in Uri, Jammu and Kashmir, and extends its sincere condolences to those who lost their lives and their bereaved families, and expresses its heartfelt sympathy to those who were injured.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Japan, Russia condemns Uri terror attack, express solidarity with India|url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/japan-russia-condemns-uri-terror-attack-express-solidarity-154319032.html|accessdate=20 September 2016|publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]|date=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Maldives}}&nbsp;\u2013 Maldives{{who|date=September 2016}} condemned the attack, saying that it has \"always condemned international terrorism, especially those originating from outside, defeating and eliminating which requires international collaboration and cooperation in good faith.\"<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Mauritius}}&nbsp;\u2013 Mauritius{{who|date=September 2016}} condemned the attack and said that it \"stands in solidarity with the Government of India and with all those committed to the fight against terrorism.\"<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Mongolia}}&nbsp;\u2013 Mongolia{{who|date=September 2016}} expressed its deep regret in regards to the attack and said that the \"terrorist attack must not be a disruption of efforts for strengthening the regional stability and mutual understanding in the region.\"<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Nepal}}&nbsp;\u2013 In a message to his Indian counterpart, Prime Minister [[Pushpa Kamal Dahal|Prachanda]] said he was of the firm belief that the perpetrators behind this heinous act will be brought to justice at the earliest. He reiterated the Nepali government's position of unequivocally condemning non-state militancy in all its forms and manifestations and said that such acts must be firmly and resolutely dealt with. Prachanda also extended his heartfelt condolences and sympathies to the bereaved families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indialivetoday.com/nepal-condemns-uri-attack/32471.html|title=Nepal condemns Uri attack|date=19 September 2016|work=indialivetoday.com|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322125741/http://www.indialivetoday.com/nepal-condemns-uri-attack/32471.html|archive-date=22 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mofa.gov.np/press-release-terrorist-attack-uri/|title=Press Release on the Terrorist Attack in Uri|date=2016-09-19|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-20}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Qatar}}&nbsp;\u2013 Qatar{{who|date=September 2016}} condemned the attack, stressing its \"condemnation of such criminal acts which aim to undermine security and stability.\"<ref name=ibt>{{cite news|last1=Bhat|first1=Aditya|title=International community supports India, strongly condemns Uri attack|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/uri-attack-here-how-international-community-responded-694476|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=21 September 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Russia}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Russian Foreign Ministry issued a statement condemning the attacks, and also offered condolences to the families of victims. The Ministry also expressed concern about the terrorist attacks near the Line of Control stating, \"We are also concerned about the fact that, according to New Delhi, the army base near Uri was attacked from Pakistani territory.\" The ministry added, \"We believe that this criminal act will be investigated properly, and that its organisers and perpetrators will be held accountable. We confirm our continued support for the Indian government's counterterrorism efforts.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Korablinov|first1=Alexander|title=Russia strongly condemns Uri attack|url=https://in.rbth.com/world/2016/09/19/russia-strongly-condemns-uri-attack_631299|website=Russia & India Report|accessdate=29 September 2016|language=en-IN|date=19 September 2016}}</ref> On 19 September, Indian media claimed that Russia was cancelling a joint military exercise with Pakistan that had been scheduled to begin on 24 September.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uri Attack fallout: Russia calls off military exercise with Pakistan|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/uri-attack-fallout-russia-calls-of-military-exercise-with-pakistan/382372/|website=The Financial Express|accessdate=29 September 2016|date=19 September 2016}}</ref> However, Russian forces arrived in Pakistan on 23 September and commenced the exercises as scheduled.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1186889/russian-forces-arrive-pakistan-first-ever-joint-military-exercise/|title=Russian forces arrive in Pakistan for first-ever joint military exercise|work=Express Tribune|date=23 September 2016|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Saudi Arabia}}&nbsp;\u2013 Saudi Arabia{{who|date=September 2016}} expressed its \"strong condemnation and denunciation of the terrorist attack that targeted an Indian military base in the Uri area of north Kashmir, killing and wounding dozens.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Caution and clamour on Uri response|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1160921/jsp/nation/story_109374.jsp#.V-KMklR97IU|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|date=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Singapore}}&nbsp;\u2013 Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] condemned the attack during an official visit to India on 4 October. \"Singapore condemns terrorism in all forms and we express condolences to the victims of the terror attack in Uri.\"<ref name=\"Singapore\">{{cite news|title=Singapore condemns terrorism in all forms|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/singapore-condemns-terrorism-in-all-forms/article9184259.ece|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=|agency=The Hindu|date=4 October 2016|location=}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Sri Lanka}}&nbsp;\u2013 President [[Maithripala Sirisena]] called PM Modi to condemn the attack and offered condolences to the families of the victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PMOIndia/status/778224808345542658|title=PMO India on Twitter|work=Twitter|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> The Foreign Ministry issued a statement that read the attack and reaffirmed the \"urgent need for sustained\" regional and global cooperation to eliminate terrorism. \"In the hour of grief, the Government of Sri Lanka offers its condolences to the families of the victims of the attack.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/india/sri-lanka-condemns-terror-attack-in-kashmirs-uri_1931268.html|title=Sri Lanka condemns terror attack in Kashmir's Uri|work=Zee News|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> On 30 September, Sri Lanka postponed its participation for the SAARC summit, saying the prevailing environment in the region was not conducive.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/south-asia/now-sri-lanka-pulls-out-of-saarc-summit/article9168393.ece Another jolt to Pakistan as Sri Lanka pulls out of SAARC Summit], The Hindu, 1 October 2016</ref>\n* {{flag|South Korea}}&nbsp;\u2013 South Korea{{who|date=September 2016}} extended its \"deepest condolences and sympathy to the innocent victims of the terrorist attack and their bereaved families,\" adding that terrorism is an unjustifiable crime against humanity.<ref name=ibt/>\n* {{flag|Turkey}}&nbsp;\u2013 Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement expressing sorrow over the \"heinous attack,\" extending its condolences \"to the families of soldiers who lost their lives\" and wishing those injured a speedy recovery. The ministry said it was \"deeply concerned about the increasing tension and casualties occurring recently in Jammu and Kashmir,\" and expressed hope that problems would be \"settled through dialogue and within the framework of the relevant UN resolutions.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-229_-18-september-2016_-press-release-regarding-the-terrorist-attack-perpetrated-in-jammu-and-kashmir.en.mfa | title=No: 229, 18 September 2016, Press Release Regarding the Terrorist Attack Perpetrated in Jammu and Kashmir | work=Turkish Ministry of Foreign Affairs | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=20 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919132836/http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-229_-18-september-2016_-press-release-regarding-the-terrorist-attack-perpetrated-in-jammu-and-kashmir.en.mfa | archive-date=19 September 2016 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* {{flag|UAE}}&nbsp;\u2013 The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation issued a statement \"renewing the nation's firm stand against terrorism in all its forms and manifestations, its solidarity with the Republic of India and its support to all actions it may take to confront and eradicate terrorism\". It further offered deepest condolences and sympathy to the families of the victims, as well as the government and people of India, and wished a speedy recovery to those who had been injured.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wam.ae/en/news/emirates-international/1395300099805.html | title=UAE condemns terrorist attack against Indian military base in Kashmir | work=Emirates News Agency | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=18 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918201320/http://www.wam.ae/en/news/emirates-international/1395300099805.html | archive-date=18 September 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* {{flag|United Kingdom}}&nbsp;\u2013 Foreign Secretary [[Boris Johnson]] condemned the attack. \"The UK strongly condemns this morning's terrorist attack in Indian-administered Kashmir. I offer my deepest condolences to the victims and their families and friends. The UK condemns all forms of terrorism, and stands shoulder to shoulder with India in the fight against terrorism, and in bringing the perpetrators to justice.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-press-release-foreign-secretary-condemns-attack-in-indian-administered-kashmir | title=FCO Press Release: Foreign Secretary condemns attack in Indian-administered Kashmir | work=Gov.uk | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|United States}}&nbsp;\u2013 State Department spokesperson [[John Kirby (admiral)|John Kirby]] said: \"The United States strongly condemns the terrorist attack on an Indian army base in Kashmir during the early morning of September 18. We extend our condolences to the victims and their families. The United States is committed to our strong partnership with the Indian government to combat terrorism.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2016/09/262053.htm | title=Indian Army Brigade Headquarters in Uri | work=U.S. Department of State | date=18 September 2016 | accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n: The Chairman of the [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade|US House Subcommittee on Terrorism]], Congressman [[Ted Poe]] from Texas, along with [[Dana Rohrabacher]] from California, introduced a bill in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] calling for a declaration of Pakistan as a \"state sponsor of terrorism.\" The bill HR6069 requires the president to issue a report within 90 days detailing Pakistan's role in supporting international terrorism followed by discussion from the [[US Secretary of State]]. Ted Poe said in a statement that Pakistan was not only an untrustworthy ally but it has also aided and abetted the enemies of the United States. He called the Uri attack the \"latest consequence of Pakistan's longstanding irresponsible policy of supporting and providing operational space for '[[jihad]]i' terrorist groups\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1185650/us-lawmakers-move-bill-designate-pakistan-terrorist-state/|title=US lawmakers move bill to designate Pakistan a terrorist state|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref><ref>\n[http://poe.house.gov/2016/9/chairman-poe-introduces-the-pakistan-state-sponsor-of-terrorism-designation-act Chairman Poe introduces the Pakistan State Sponsor of Terrorism Designation Act], Press release, U. S. Congressman Ted Poe (official website), 20 September 2016.\n</ref>\n: {{flag|Venezuela}}&nbsp;\u2013 [[President of Venezuela|Venezuelan President]] [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] expressed solidarity with the people of India and stated: \"We are committed along with our brotherly people of the world to get into the depth of this problem that has generated proliferation of terrorist movements, which doesn't respect life and the need for coexistence of people.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/un-secretary-general-ban-ki-moon-condemns-uri-terror-attack/articleshow/54402038.cms | title=UN Secretary General Ban Ki-moon condemns Uri terror attack | work=Economic Times | date=19 September 2016 | accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Supranational bodies===\n* {{flag|EU}}&nbsp;\u2013 An EU spokesperson issued a statement calling for solidarity against non-state militancy and expressing condolences to the families of the victims of the attack. \"Yesterday's terrorist attack against the Uri Indian military camp demonstrates once again that terrorism has no boundaries, and that it is a global threat. As far as the European Union is concerned, we are committed to working with our partners and the international community at large to combat terrorism in all its forms. Our first thoughts and condolences go to the victims of this attack and to their families. We wish a quick recovery to those who were injured.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eeas.europa.eu/node/10040_en|title=Attack at the Indian Army Camp in Uri&nbsp;\u2013 eeas&nbsp;\u2013 European Commission|author=|date=|work=europa.eu}}</ref>\n* {{flag|UN}}&nbsp;\u2013 On 19 September, [[Ban Ki-moon]], the spokesperson of the [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]], issued a statement which condemned the attack and expressed his deepest sympathy and condolences to the families of the soldiers who lost their lives and to the government of India. He also wished a speedy recovery to those who were injured during the attack and hoped that the perpetrators of the army base will be identified and brought to justice.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/uri-attack-un-secretary-general-ban-ki-moon-condemns-3038462/ | title=Uri terror attack: UN Secretary General Ban Ki-moon condemns act| work=The Indian Express | date=19 September 2016 | accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\nThe ''[[Deutsche Welle]]'' noted that Kashmir was already in international headlines at the time of the Uri attack due to the anti-India protests. It further noted that immediately after the attack, [[mainstream media]] in India and Pakistan engaged in \"angry\" rhetoric towards each other.<ref name=DWmedia>{{cite news|title=How Indian and Pakistani media are covering Kashmir unrest|url=http://www.dw.com/en/how-indian-and-pakistani-media-are-covering-kashmir-unrest/a-19562791}}</ref> A video of Indian soldiers chanting \"Pakistan, hear this loud and clear: If ... war breaks out you will be obliterated\" went viral. ''[[The Diplomat]]'' noted that many Indian media had openly called for a war on Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Could India and Pakistan Go to War?|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/09/could-india-and-pakistan-go-to-war/}}</ref>\n\n''[[India Today]]'' suggested that the fallout from the Uri attack would hurt Pakistani artists in India.<ref name=ITartist>{{cite news|title=Uri aftermath: Pakistan artists to be banned in India?|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/indo-pak-tension-break-cultural-ties/1/772653.html}}</ref> [[Maharashtra Navnirman Sena]] gave all Pakistani artists in India 48 hours to leave the country and warned that they would be \"hunted down\".<ref name=IndiaExpressArtists>{{cite news|title=Zee Entertainment Enterprises|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/All-Pakistani-artists-have-left-Mumbai-will-hunt-down-whoever-is-still-left-MNS/2016/09/25/article3629539.ece}}</ref> [[Subhash Chandra]] also said Pakistani artists should leave.<ref name=ITartist/> [[Zee Entertainment Enterprises|Zee TV]] considered terminating Pakistani shows. The Indian Motion Picture Producers Association (IMPPA) decided to ban all Pakistani actors, actresses and technicians in India till the situation returned to normal.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> However Bollywood artists were divided towards the ban with some justifying it while some questioning its benefits.<ref name=\"firstpost.com\"/>\n\nOn 18 September, the [[Times of India]] revealed that the army personnel recovered a map from the attackers which had markings in the [[Pashtun language]] and indicated a detailed plan of action. Four [[AK-47]] rifles and four [[grenade launcher|under barrel grenade launchers]] along with ammunition were also recovered. According to the Indian Army, some of the items had Pakistani markings.<ref name=web/> This was denied by the [[National Investigation Agency]].\n\n''[[The Diplomat]]'' noted that the timing of the attack coincided with the Pakistani Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]]'s visit to New York to address the [[United Nations General Assembly]] the following week.<ref name=Diplomat>\nShawn Snow, [http://thediplomat.com/2016/09/17-indian-soldiers-killed-in-kashmir-india-pakistan-tensions-heating-up/ 17 Indian Soldiers Killed in Kashmir: India-Pakistan Tensions Heating up], The Diplomat, 19 September 2016.\n</ref> ''[[The Diplomat]]'', in another article, said that the attack was \"designed\" to increase public pressure against the Modi government's engagement with Pakistan.<ref name=Panda/>\n\nIt also reported that there was specific intelligence input from the [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] two days earlier that an attack was being planned against army formations close to the LOC.<ref>\n[https://www.thequint.com/uri-attack/2016/09/21/uri-avenged-2-india-paras-special-forces-cross-loc-uri-sector-jammu-and-kashmir-pakistan-neutralise-20-terrorists Exclusive: Uri Avenged As Spl Forces Cross LoC, Kill 20 Terrorists, report Chandan Nandy], The Quint, 22 September 2016.\n</ref> The intelligence agency had said that three ''fidayeen'' squads were launched from [[Pakistan-administered Kashmir]]. One of them attacked Uri, another went to [[Poonch (town)|Poonch]] where it was engaged by the security forces, and the third is believed to be targeting Srinagar highway.<ref name=intel>\n[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/uri-attack-specific-intelligence-inputs-ib-alert-army-units/1/767204.html Uri attack: There was specific intelligence inputs; IB alerted army units on Thursday], India Today, 18 September 2016.\n</ref> The [[India Today Television]] mentioned that, according to unnamed intelligence sources, Pakistan was plotting a \"spectacular event\" ahead of Nawaz Sharif's speech to the UN General Assembly.<ref>\n[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/video/pakistan-nawaz-sharif-un-speech-intel-sources/1/767147.html Uri attack: Pakistan plots spectacular event ahead of Sharif's UN speech, report Intel sources], India Today Television, 19 September 2016.\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n* [[2016 Indian Line of Control strike]] (Indian retaliation to this attack)\n* [[List of terrorist incidents in India]]\n* [[Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir]]\n* [[India-Pakistan Relations]]\n*[[Uri: The Surgical Strike|Uri T